<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Election Commission Calls for National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Electoral Supervisory
Commission Wednesday urged the government and the opposition
National Constitutional Assembly (NCA) to seek national
compromise, saying it is the only way to break the impasse in
constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
The commission Chairman Peter Hatendi told the Zimbabwe News
Agency that it was "beyond any doubt" that the two feuding sides
could not proceed without the other and claim to have national
support.
</P>
<P>
The government is insisting on drawing up a new constitution
under the Commission of Inquiry Act while the National
Constitutional Assembly, a grouping of opposition parties and
civic groups, is opposed to the commission being set up by the
president for fear that it would be manipulated.
</P>
<P>
The Constitutional Assembly has demanded that a legal
framework, binding all parties to stick to the outcome of reforms,
be put in place.
</P>
<P>
"There is mutual mistrust on both sides hence the reluctance to
give in to demands from the other group. The government fears
losing power to the NCA and the NCA fears allowing the government
to produce a constitution that gives all the power to the ruling
party," Hatendi said.
</P>
<P>
"But since both groups seem interested in coming up with a
constitution acceptable to the whole nation and no later than now,
then they should find a middle of the road solution to the
sticking points," he said.
</P>
<P>
The commission also supports the government that a new
constitution be in place before the next general elections early
next year.
</P>
<P>
The NCA has been arguing that constitutional reforms should not
be linked to forthcoming elections as it was a process meant to
provide a permanent framework of Zimbabwe's nationhood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
