<HEADLINE> Zambia Urges SADC to Care More About Airline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Zambia called on the civil aviation
in Southern Africa Development Community (SADC) region on
Wednesday not to compromise safety for the sake of commercial
considerations.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Deputy Minister for Communication and Transport Mann
Muyuni made the appeal while opening the second civil aviation
commercial meeting for SADC Transport and Communications
Commission in Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
The official called for the establishment of adequate and
reliable infrastructure to support the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
He noted that although a number of carriers have changed in
line with the liberalization of the industry, this has not changed
the safety of the skies.
</P>
<P>
Muyuni cautioned the commission from cost cutting at the
expense of safety which was of paramount importance, but called
for the standardization of civil aviation to make it competitive.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister revealed that Zambian government was in the
 process of restructuring its civil aviation in order to make it
effective and more responsive to meet the involving challenges of
the civil aviation industry in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said it is sad to see that passengers at some airports are
still subjected to practices which hinder them to travel freely
such as long queues to pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
There was need to find ways and means which should be worked
out to remove blocks to passengers so that they are provided with
quick check in and out, he urged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
