<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moral Education Underlined to Prevent AIDS in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 7 (Xinhua) -- An advisor to the United Nations
Wednesday urged the Kenyan government to launch a moral education
campaign among children to curb the spread of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
To date prevention focused on the use of condom and education
of awareness is not effective in Africa, said Farzin Davachi,
medical advisor and consultant to the World Health Organization
(WHO), World Bank and Pan American Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
The focus should shift to moral education, abstinence before
marriage and faithfulness afterwards, he said, adding that the
Center for Disease Control of the United States have declared
that "the surest way to prevent AIDS is abstinence" after its 15
years of trial and evaluation since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Moral education should concentrate on children since it is
difficult to change an adult's behavior, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
The effectiveness of moral education is demonstrated by Uganda,
which is one of the few countries in Africa where AIDS has leveled
 off and may be decreasing, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government has fulfilled moral education programs
among children since late 1980s. Moral education and sex
education have been required subjects in primary schools since
then.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan senior officials and media should pay much more
attention and space to the AIDS epidemic, he said.
</P>
<P>
The infection rate of HIV/AIDS in Kenya stands at 10 percent
among the 15-49 age group. More than half of medical beds in
Kenya's hospitals are occupied by people suffering from AIDS and
AIDS-related illness.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Health Organization, HIV/AIDS has
infected over 34 million people worldwide and two thirds of those
are in sub-Saharan Africa. East African region is the
hardest-hit region in the world.
</P>
<P>
Davachi is visiting Kenya on a mission to sensitize the
country to the dangers of AIDS and help the Kenyan government
reevaluate their AIDS prevention programs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
