<HEADLINE> Security Council to Continue Consultations on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council will continue its consultations on Iraq Friday which began
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council embarked on the critical discussions this
morning by reviewing reports by three U.N. panels on Iraq which
was set up according to a January 30 note of the Security Council.
The discussions should lead to political decisions on future arms
monitoring in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Council President Alain Dejammet of
France said the Council members expressed their gratitude to the
efforts the panels had made and the work they had done.
</P>
<P>
Dejammet said the Council had just begun its process of forming
new U.N. policy towards Iraq and the Council would continue this
process on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The first panel, on disarmament concluded that not all Iraqi
weapons of mass destruction had been dismantled, notably in the
biological field.
</P>
<P>
The second panel, on humanitarian situation, called for the
loosening of the economic sanctions through a series of
recommendations aimed at pumping more money into the underfunded
humanitarian oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
The third panel, on prisoners of war and Kuwaiti property, said
that Iraq had not fully complied with requirements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
