<HEADLINE> Ugandan Parliament Demands More Actions Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan parliament has adopted
the report of the select committee on agriculture, animal industry
and fisheries, demanding more actions against corrupt officials.
</P>
<P>
The over-100-page long report, which prompted the recent major
cabinet reshuffle by President Yoweri Museveni, was adopted by the
House Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The report, together with a number of resolutions, demands
action from the government.
</P>
<P>
One of the key resolutions demands that the government report
back to the House actions taken within three months.
</P>
<P>
The report, which took the committee 90 days to prepare and
three weeks to debate, also demands that all officers of the
Ministry of Agriculture who may have caused financial loss be
interdicted, investigated and dismissed from the civil service if
found guilty.
</P>
<P>
However, a motion seeking to extend the life of the select
committee to enable it investigate the remaining 55 projects in
the same ministry was defeated.
</P>
<P>
In the latest cabinet reshuffle, Vice President Specioza
Kazibwe was removed from the agricultural portfolio. Several
other ministers including Sam Kutesa, who got censured by the
parliament recently, were axed from the new cabinet list.
</P>
<P>
The reactions to the cabinet reshuffle were mixed. While some
commended the president for the bold move, others thought what he
had done is far from enough.
</P>
<P>
There is a loud outcry in the parliament for the officials
suspected of being corrupt, incompetent, to be suspended while
investigations against them are under way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
