<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Flirt With New Peak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON April 7 (Xinhua) - European stock markets flirted with
new peaks Wednesday as the European Central Bank and the Bank of
England are expected to cut interest rate and a firm opening on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Buoyed by a lightning surge in bank stocks, which accounted for
90 percent of the point gain in the main index, the FTSE 100
advanced 57.9 points to 6473.2.
</P>
<P>
The financial sector as usual was at the forefront of the
rises. Abbey National was the biggest riser gaining 77p followed
by Halifax up 48.5p to 850p.
</P>
<P>
The telecoms sector, which had helped drive the rise, put in
another strong performance after Cable &AMP; Wireless Communication and
Telewest Communications confirmed they were in potential merger
talks.
</P>
<P>
Germany's blue-chip share index held onto most gains, although
dealers warned that thin volumes were exaggerating moves.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Telekom was the most actively traded stock with gains
of more than 2 percent before it slipped back a little. The Xetra
Dax closed up 4.98 at 5027.25 points.
</P>
<P>
French retail stocks progressed on the day but the broader
market fell back from a similar advance as uncertainty clouded
hopes for a European rate cut and the Dow gave up some of its
early gains.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 closed up 0.3 percent at 4318.04 in a volume of
1.8bn euros, tracking back from its day-high of 4351.80, just
inches from 1999's peak of 4354.29, set on 1 February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
