<HEADLINE> Man Admits to "Mardi Gra" Bomb Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A 61-year-old man from London on
Wednesday admitted to being the Mardi Gra bomber who attempted
blackmail against Barclays Bank and Sainsbury's supermarkets in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Edgar Pearce pleaded guilty at London's Old Bailey to 20
charges, including possessing firearms and explosives, wounding
and several blackmail attempts from December 1994 to April 1998,
when he was arrested. He will be sentenced at a later date.
</P>
<P>
There were more than 33 incidents in and around London since
the Mardi Gra bomber first struck in December 1994.
</P>
<P>
One person was seriously hurt by the devices planted by Pearce
in an attempt to extort money. Police at the time feared the
attacker was prepared to cause injury and death.
</P>
<P>
In the first attack, bombs were sent to six London branches of
Barclays Bank in video cassette boxes. Three people were injured
when some of the devices exploded.
</P>
<P>
Pearce was arrested after he visited a bank machine, in a
surveillance operation involving 1,000 police officers.
</P>
<P>
The exact amount the bomber demanded has not been made public
but it was reported to be about 10 million pounds (16.6 million
U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
