<HEADLINE> U.S. Threatens Yugoslav Commanders for War Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Wednesday
threatened to bring nine Yugoslav commanders to the international
war crimes tribunal.
</P>
<P>
"We are naming the commanders as a warning to them that the
world is watching, and that the war crimes tribunal is there and
we are going to assist them in this process," State Department
spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said it was up to the International War Crimes Tribunal
whether or not to indict anyone suspected of war crimes, but said
the United States would be providing the tribunal with detailed
information and names.
</P>
<P>
The United States has never mentioned the NATO bombing has
caused more than one thousand of civilian lives in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also said there appeared no ceasefire in Kosovo after
Belgrade made the ceasefire offer on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We... are not yet in a position to confirm that such a
ceasefire is in place," he said.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade on Tuesday declared a unilateral ceasefire in the
conflict with NATO that began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
But the alliance rejected it and said it would continue air
strikes until Yugoslavia complies with NATO demands, including
acceptance of Western troops' deployment in Kosovo, a Yugoslav
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
