<HEADLINE>      Russia Supports Conclusions of UN Panels on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Wednesday voiced
its support for the conclusions of the three U.N. panels on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Sergev Lavrov, Russia's Ambassador to
the United Nations, said "We do believe that we have to move to a
new monitoring regime which would be allowing for an enhanced
monitoring presence in Iraq and which would also allow in that
context to solve whatever disarmament issues might remain, and this
should be done in conjunction with lifting sanctions..."
</P>
<P>
The Security Council this morning embarked on the critical
discussions on Iraq by reviewing reports by three U.N. panels on
Iraq which was set up according to a January 30 note of the
Security Council. The discussions should lead to political
decisions on future arms monitoring in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The first panel, on disarmament concluded that not all Iraqi
weapons of mass destruction had been dismantled, notably in the
biological field. It recommended that intrusive inspections
under a monitoring program needed to resume in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The second panel, on humanitarian situation, called for the
loosening of the economic sanctions through a series of
recommendations aimed at pumping more money into the underfunded
humanitarian oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
The third panel, on prisoners of war and Kuwaiti property,
said that Iraq had not fully complied with requirements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
