<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Business Confidence Edges Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The South African business
mood improved slightly in March for the second month in a row,
helped by favorable financial environment both at home and abroad,
the South African Chamber of Business said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The chamber's monthly Business Confidence Index increased by
0,9 points to 84,5 in March from 83.6 in February.
</P>
<P>
The improvement, while still vulnerable, augured well for a
further cut in interest rates soon, said the chamber.
</P>
<P>
The positive developments in the economy were mainly in the
financial environment. Easier domestic monetary conditions and
relative stable international financial markets contributed to
these circumstances, it said.
</P>
<P>
Among positive factors signaling a possible economic upswing
later this year were lower inflation, the resumption of foreign
capital flows into bonds and equities, lower import and higher
export volumes, higher share prices and higher vehicle sales.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion of the free trade deal with the European Union
also helped business sentiment.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, the gold price and South African currency rand
exchange rate declined slightly, and both manufacturing volumes
and retail sales fell.
</P>
<P>
The country was in desperate need of improved economic
performance and it was therefore absolutely imperative that the
growth potential of the economy should be enhanced by the
continuation of a prudent macro-economic policy and by addressing
the remaining structural deficiencies, said the chamber of
business.
</P>
<P>
Describing the immediate economic outlook as "subdued", the
chamber said that the election campaign, crime and violence, and
unforeseen developments on the international economic scene, as
well as the Balkans war and the dollar oil price, could all
influence business confidence in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
The domestic economy remained sluggish with high debt levels,
although the decline was slowing down, it said.
</P>
<P>
While it was too early to tell whether the latest increase in
business confidence represented a fundamental shift out of
negative territory, there were enough positive indications to
suggest that the economy was heading for the lower turning point
in the downward phase of the current business cycle, said the
chamber.
</P>
<P>
South Africa "could start to experience the benefits later in
the year for which the present more positive business mood is
paving the way," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
