<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Join SADC Exercise Blue Crane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 7 (Xinhua) (C Tanzania will send a team of
some 200 soldiers Thursday to South Africa to join their partners
from the South African Development Community (SADC) countries in a
peacekeeping exercise.
</P>
<P>
The Spokesman of the Ministry of Defense and National Service
told reporters here Wednesday that the training, code-named
Exercise Blue Crane, is aimed at enhancing the capacity of the
SADC military forces for peace support operations.
</P>
<P>
Brigadier General Sylvester Rioba said that all the SADC
members except the Democratic Republic of Congo will participate
the exercise at the Army Battle School in Lohatla, South Africa,
from next Wednesday to April 30.
</P>
<P>
An advance part of the Tanzania People's Defense Forces (TPDF)
soldiers, led by Brigadier General Christopher Gimonge, will leave
Thursday aboard Air India while the rest will follow later, he
said. !0This group training has much to do with confidence
building among soldiers in the SADC region,!1 Rioba said. !0It
will be conducted under universal standing operation procedures
for the member countries.!1
</P>
<P>
He said that soldiers from Tanzania, Angola, Botswana, Lesotho,
Malawi, Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, Seychelles, Zambia, South
Africa and Zimbabwe will use their own weaponry and foot
participation expenses.  
</P>
</TEXT>
