<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Do They Take Everything for Military? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NIS, Yugoslavia, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Some 10 cruise missiles
and bombs fell on Nis early Wednesday during the fifth round of
NATO air strikes against this central Serbian city.
</P>
<P>
All missiles and bombs hit their targets but none of the
targets were military.
</P>
<P>
The hit targets were the Elektrotehna Shop, Fidelinka
Warehouse, Duvana Cigarette Factory, Subotica Pasta Factory and
Jastrebac Pump Factory.
</P>
<P>
Shock waves from the blasts also damaged adjacent civilian
buildings including residences, schools and libraries.
</P>
<P>
The shop-keepers who went to work Wednesday morning only found
that their shop was completely destroyed. In the courtyard of the
shop was a huge bomb crater measuring 13 meters in diameter and 8
meters in depth.
</P>
<P>
Water from ruptured underground pipes filled more than half of
the crater while the clay from the crater was thrown and strewn
everywhere, even across the one-storey shop itself to cover the
surface of the roads 10 meters in front of the shop.
</P>
<P>
All glasses on the doors and windows of the shop were shattered
and the ceilings caved in and the tiles on the roof slid down to
the ground.
</P>
<P>
Covered by clay, dirt and shards of glasses were goods which
were supposed to be on display on the shelves but were now lying
on the floor inside the shop.
</P>
<P>
The goods included electric fans, washing machines, electronic
cookers, electrical motors, electricity wires, lamps, bulbs,
hair-driers, bolts and screws.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 meters away, one NATO bomb hit a warehouse of the
Duvana Cigarette Factory, where 1,000 tons of bundles of dried
tobacco leaves were still spewing smoke into the sky.
</P>
<P>
The entire roof collapsed onto piles of bundles of tobacco
leaves and broken steel reinforcement wires were distorted and
twisted.
</P>
<P>
Jovan Zlatic, director of the Nis Civil Defense Center, said
that the NATO attacks on Wednesday hit no other targets than
civilian buildings.
</P>
<P>
"Do NATO aggressors take everything for military targets?" he
asked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
