<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breast Cancer May Be More Than Just One Disease: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Different grades of breast tumor
may actually represent different types of breast tumor, British
scientists have suggested.
</P>
<P>
A study by scientists from UK's Imperial Cancer Research Fund
showed that breast tumors, which have generally been thought to
form a single category, may actually belong to different
sub-groups with different origins.
</P>
<P>
If the research is further confirmed, "the various tumor types
should offer different targets against which to develop new and
more specific drug treatments." the Imperial Cancer Research Fund
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Doctors usually grade breast tumors from I to III according to
the microscopic appearance of samples taken from suspicious lumps
with grade I the least aggressive.
</P>
<P>
However, new study by Dr Rebecca Roylance and colleagues
strongly suggested that what the grading system describes is not
the progress of a single tumor type, but existence of different
types.
</P>
<P>
"It was about ten years ago that people began to question the
meaning of these grades," said Dr Roylance, who works in Imperial
Cancer Research Fund's Human Cytogenetics and Breast Pathology
Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
But Roylance said they found that if a primary tumor is treated
and then recurs, it tends to come back as the same grade.
</P>
<P>
After comparing the genetic make-up of 40 grade I tumors with
that of 50 grade IIIs, the researchers found that genetic changes
found on grade I tumors were not always found on grade III tumors,
which contradicted common predictions.
</P>
<P>
"It's unclear why some women get a grade I and others a grade
III tumor, but it's likely that there will be more than one
reason," Dr Roylance said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Sees More Prolonged Crisis in Emerging Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Average growth rates in
developing and transition countries are likely to fall to just 1.5
percent in 1999, down from 1.9 percent in 1998, and 4.8 percent in
1997, making it the lowest growth rate since 1982, the World Bank
said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a report entitled Global Development Finance 1999, the bank
blamed the slowing growth in emerging markets on declining trade
growth, slumping commodity prices, and tightened long-term
financing caused by the global financial crisis, which started in
East Asia nearly two years ago, spread to Russia, and sent shocks
to Brazil late last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, world trade growth slowed to 4.6 percent, compared
with 10 percent in 1997. Prices for primary commodity exports,
excluding oil, fell 16 percent. And net long-term finance dropped
by 58 billion U.S. dollars, while interest rate spreads for these
loans soared.
</P>
<P>
While the impact of these factors varies widely among
countries, their combined effect may have reduced overall demand
in developing countries by 3 to 4 percent in 1998 from 1997
levels, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, global output is forecast to slow
further in 1999, increasing by 1.8 percent, compared with a 1.9
percent increase in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Growth is expected to slow in Europe, while several large
developing countries, including China, India, and Mexico, are
expected to weather the difficult conjuncture relatively well, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, several Latin American economies, countries of the
Former Soviet Union, and Middle Eastern and African oil exporters
are forecast to face stagnation or declines in output.
</P>
<P>
Thus, global growth rates are unlikely to return to historical
trends before 2001, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that flows to developing countries from
international capital markets plunged to 72 billion dollars in
1998 compared with 136 billion dollars in 1997, as investors in
bonds, portfolio equity, and long-term bank loans retreated from
emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign direct investment (FDI) in developing
economies was more resilent, falling by less than 5 percent to 155
billion dollars in 1998 from the 1997 peak of 163 billion dollars.
Some of the East Asian crisis countries actually saw increases in
FDI despite severe recessions, as FDI was attracted by the
collapse in domestic asset prices, massive exchange rate
depreciation, and a more welcoming stance towards foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
Although financing volumes, spreads and equity prices have
recovered somewhat in recent months, developing countries' access
to the international financial markets remains limited, the World
Bank said. But FDI is likely to remain the largest source of
finance to developing countries for the foreseeable future, it
added.
</P>
<P>
The report said concessional assistance to developing countries
remained at 33 billion dollars in 1998, or one-third below the
1990 level in real terms. Official development assistance from the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development countries
has fallen to only 0.22 percent of their combined gross domestic
product (GDP), compared to 0.35 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The industrial countries had promised to contribute 0.7 percent
of their GDP as official development assistance to developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
Despite some positive development in 1998 -- notably the
progress in reducing the debt burden of the poorest, most heavily
indebted countries -- the prospects for aid remain bleak, said the
bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Says Much Needs to be Done in Forging New Policy  Towards Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The conclusion of the
assessment on Iraq was perhaps a small step, if not a big one,
towards forging a new U.N. policy on the country, U.N. said here
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the press, Celso Amorim, the chairman of the three
panels on Iraq established according to a January 30 note by the
United Nations Security Council, said there was still a long way
to go before the Council members could reach consensus on its
policy towards Iraq due to differences among them.
</P>
<P>
Amorim said his panels could only provide technical replies to
Iraqi issue and it was up to the Security Council to make
political decisions.
</P>
<P>
Amorim briefed the Council this morning on the conclusions of
his reports on Iraq which had been submitted to the Council last
week. Recommendations in the reports will be the basis for the
Council to form its new policy towards Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The first panel, on disarmament and current and future ongoing
monitoring and verification issues, recommended that intrusive
inspections under a monitoring program be needed to resume in
Iraq. It also called for a renovated or restructured U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM), now responsible for dismantling Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The second panel, on humanitarian situation, recommended
improvement and some alterations to the U.N. humanitarian
program, which allows Iraq to sell limited amounts of oil to
provide humanitarian aid for its people. It also suggested the
Council consider authorizing foreign investment to improve Iraq's
export abilities.
</P>
<P>
The third panel, on prisoners of war and Kuwaiti property,
concluded that Iraq had not provided sufficient explanations about
missing Kuwaitis or cooperated enough in returning looted
property.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. officials, the proposals had been rejected
by Iraq for several reasons. Iraq has reiterated that lifting
sanctions is the precondition for it to resume cooperation with
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Council has been sharply divided on Iraq issue since the
U.S.-led air strikes against Iraq last December.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Delegate: Dialogue Helps to Narrow Differences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has all
along maintained that different opinions on human rights should be
solved through dialogue and exchanges on the basis of equality and
mutual respect, said a Chinese delegate here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"This has been proven the most effective way," said Ambassador
Qiao Zonghui, head of the Chinese delegation, at a meeting of the
ongoing 55th session of the United Nations Commission on Human
Rights.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has noted with appreciation that the
European Union (EU) has decided, for the second time, not to
sponsor a China resolution at the current commission session, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"This is a sensible move not only for the China-EU human rights
dialogue but also for defusing the confrontation in the
commission," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Qiao said, the United States government announced on
March 26 that it would sponsor an anti-China resolution by itself
due to the so-called "sharp deterioration of China's human rights
record".
</P>
<P>
"The United States has unleashed attacks on China for trying
several criminals," he said. "And what I would like to make clear
is that these persons were arrested and tried for having engaged
in the activities subverting the state power and endangering state
security, which had nothing to do with their exercise of the
freedom of expression and association."
</P>
<P>
he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Covenant on Economic, Social and
Cultural Rights and the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights, Qiao told the session, the exercise of rights is
not unlimited.
</P>
<P>
"Instead, it is subject to due limitations in the interests of
state security, public safety, public order and the rights and
freedoms of others," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qiao predicted that the U.S.-sponsored anti-China resolution
will be doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the anti-China resolution was defeated for seven
times demonstrates that confrontation leads to nowhere," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
