<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's foreign currency reserves dropped 182
million U.S. dollars in March to 21.98 billion dollars, according
to statistics released by the Bank of Israel.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time since last November that Israel's
"mountain of dollars" has dipped below 22 billion dollars. At its
peak last December, the stash of dollars hit 22.67 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon has decided to shut down two largest citrus
packing factories because of strong foreign competition, the high
cost of production and lack of government support, the Daily Star
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Zaatari and Safa factories, both located in the Ghazieh
area south of the country's southern port city of Sidon, have
temporarily ceased operations after a sharp drop in sales of
citrus and other fruits to Arab Gulf states and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
"We were unable to maintain production after realizing that
our clients in the Gulf were buying agricultural products from
Egypt and Turkey almost 50 percent cheaper than from Lebanon,"
said Mohammed Zaatari, owner of the Zaatari plant and President
of the Sidon Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's three major cellular phone companies
spent 22 million U.S. dollars during the first quarter of this
year on advertising and promotions.
</P>
<P>
The newly-formed Partner company spent 8.3 million dollars,
excluding its massive billboard campaign expenditures during its
initial penetration period. As a result, Partner attracted 100,000
clients during this period.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz
Monday met with Chief Executive of the U.S. Marathon Oil Company
Victor Beghini to tap the potential of joint investment in the
Gulf kingdom's energy sector.
</P>
<P>
Beghini presented Abdullah his company's investment plans in
Saudi Arabia's petroleum and gas sectors, the Saudi Press Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil producer, is reluctant
to allow foreign participation in its oil and gas exploration and
production because it currently enjoys a surplus output capacity
of over 2 million barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's net foreign debt at the end of 1998 was
13.7 billion U.S. dollars, down 13 percent from that of 1997, the
Finance Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The net foreign debt to gross domestic product ratio was 15
percent at the end of 1998, and that at the beginning of 1990 was
31 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
