<HEADLINE> NATO Has No Time to Pause Air Strikes, Cohen Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen told reporters here Wednesday evening that the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) has no time to pause air
strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Cohen made the remarks at a special news briefing in
Brussels-based NATO headquarters. During the day he met with NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana, U.S. general Wesley Clark, NATO's
supreme commander in Europe, and 19 NATO ambassadors in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
He said he and the NATO leaders talked about the latest
development in Kosovo and evaluated how to take further steps and
how long the air strikes would last. The NATO was determined to
continue its air campaign, he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked if sending ground troops is one of the final choices,
Cohen said there is no plan to send ground troops in current
stage. "Both United States and NATO believe air strikes must
continue," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The defense secretary also said the objective of the military
operation remains degrading and disrupting the capability of
Yugoslav and Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said earlier that Cohen will also, in
the evening, meet with British Secretary of Defense George
Robertson, who came here on route to Germany, Solana and NATO
ambassadors to discuss Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to Pentagon spokesmen Ken Bacon, Cohen may on
Thursday visit Italy where he will meet members of the U.S. air
forces based at Aviano, which have carried out many of the air
attacks on Yugoslav forces in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
During his short trip in Europe, Cohen may also stop off at
Ramstein Air Base in Germany on his way home before weekend to
look at humanitarian operations being run from there to help
hundreds of thousandeds of ethnic Albanian refugees who have fled
into Macedonia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
Cohen left Washington Monday for his European tour with a
number of Republican and Democrat Congressmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
