<HEADLINE> Clinton Demands Yugoslavia to Meet NATO Requirements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton,
rejecting a ceasefire offer from Belgrade, insisted on Wednesday
that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic should comply with all
the demands set by NATO before a peace could be considered.
</P>
<P>
In a foreign policy speech, Clinton said Milosevic's offer of a
ceasefire was "not enough" to end NATO's air campaign against
Yugoslavia as it did not meet all the NATO's commands.
</P>
<P>
"It is not enough now for Mr. Milosevic to say that his forces
will cease fire in Kosovo," he said.
</P>
<P>
"He must withdraw his forces, let the refugees return, permit
the deployment of an international security force," he added.
"nothing less will bring peace with security to the People of
Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said they believe that recent overtures by
Yugoslavia, including the ceasefire offer, were designed to weaken
NATO resolve to use military force against Belgrade, which is
determined to protect its sovereign territory of Kosovo from being
invaded by the Western alliance.
</P>
<P>
White House officials were reacting cautiously to apparent
moves that may lead to the release of three U.S. army soldiers
captured by the Serb forces last week.
</P>
<P>
White House National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said he
could not confirm the soldiers would be freed. Washington has
called for the release of these soldiers since their capture last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly would welcome the release of the three American
soldiers. I can't confirm that that will take place," Berger
told NBC's "Today" program. 
</P>
