<HEADLINE> Most Iraqi Contracts on Hold: Iraq Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Only 40 percent of the contracts
Iraq signed with foreign companies in the current phase of the
oil-for-food deal were approved by the U.N. Sanctions Committee,
an Iraqi official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh also
said that the six-month fifth phase will expire on May 25, but
many contracts for electricity, water, sanitation and education
sectors have yet to be approved, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The contracts Iraq signed with foreign companies will not be
allowed to be implemented until they are approved by the
U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
Saleh said Iraq has in its credit 250 million U.S. dollars,
enough to cover the contracts of the current phase, but the
U.S. and British representatives at the U.N. Sanctions Committee
are still creating "pretexts and lies" to impede the approval of
the deals.
</P>
<P>
The U.N., which imposed sanctions on Iraq following its 1990
invasion of Kuwait, allows Iraq to export limited amount of oil
every six months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
To increase Iraq's oil production and export capacity, the
U.N., since the fourth stage, has allowed Iraq to import 300
million dollars of spare parts badly needed in the country's
dilapidated oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Saleh stressed that many contracts Iraq concluded in the fourth
phase are still on hold.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has long accused the U.S. and British representative at
the U.N. Sanctions Committee, or 661 committee, of blocking the
approval of the contracts it signed with foreign companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
