<HEADLINE> Lebanon Seeks U.N. Intervention in Israeli Expulsion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese leaders on Wednesday
called on the United Nations to intervene to help Lebanese
residents expelled by Israeli forces return to their homes in
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Nabih Berri sent a telegram to the U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan, asking him to step in and get those deportees
back to their homes, the official National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Israeli forces expelled 25 Lebanese residents,
mostly elderly, children and women, from their village of Shebaa
in the eastern sector of the Israeli occupied border zone in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The expulsion came in response to Monday's desertion of four
militiamen of the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA).
</P>
<P>
All of the deportees are relatives of the four defectors who
reportedly sneaked out of Shebaa through the hills at dawn and
turned themselves in to the Lebanese army.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Salim Hoss instructed Lebanon's representatives
in the U.N. to distribute among the U.N. member states a document
concerning Israeli "barbaric" practices against Lebanese civilians.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he asked authorities concerned to set up camps for
the deportees on the border between the Israeli occupied enclave
and the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
There are currently nearly 2,500 SLA members, who are helping
Israeli forces to patrol its occupied zone and handling the
security affairs in Jezzine, a predominantly Christian town facing
the enclave.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen were considered as traitors in Lebanon and its
commander Antonie Lahd has been sentenced to death in absentia by
a Lebanese military court.
</P>
<P>
Amid mounting speculation that Israeli forces may conduct a
unilateral partial withdrawal from south Lebanon, the SLA's morale
is sinking and more members are defecting to the Lebanese
government to escape future reprisals.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-proclaimed security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 to "protect" its north from Lebanese guerrillas'
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by Shiite
Muslim group Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been fighting to oust
Israeli forces and their allied militia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
