<HEADLINE> Annan Has No Intention to Jump into Kosovo Crisis, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- As NATO is mounting air
strikes on Yugoslavia, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Anna "has no
intention of jumping into a (Kosovo) crisis, where he doesn't have
useful role to play," a U.N. spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In response to a press question, Fred Eckhard, U.N. spokesman,
said the six-nation Contact Group, which is in charge of the
Balkan diplomacy, "is taking a lead" in addressing the crisis of
Kosovo, a Serbian province in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"Frankly, there's a war going on," he said, "he (Annan) would
like to hold himself in reserve if at any time there appears to be
a useful role for him to play."
</P>
<P>
"Right now, he concentrating on the humanitarian side," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The statement by the U.N. spokesman echoed a Monday statement
by Annan, who said that the present role of the United Nations is
to render massive relief operations, and the United Nations High
Commission for Refugees is leading the operation in the region.
</P>
<P>
The world media, including the U.S. newspapers, carried stories
that said the 185-member world body has been sidelined by the
U.S.-led NATO, which began unilateral air attacks on Yugoslavia on
March 24.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Annan is visiting Geneva, where he delivered
speeches at the meeting of the Chairman/Coordinators of the Group
of 77 Chapters and the U.N. Human Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment, the United Nations is not involved at all on
the military side. But one cannot tell what happens tomorrow, as
one searches for a long-term solution," Annan told a press
conference Wednesday in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
"What we need at the moment is to focus on the refugees, get
them to shelter, protect their rights, and take steps to ensure
that they will be able to go back home in safety," he said.
</P>
<P>
A large exodus of refugees followed massive NATO air strikes on
Yugoslavia, a sovereign and independent member of the U.N. family.
</P>
</TEXT>
