<HEADLINE> Simple Kitchen Appliance May Help Fight Food-Poisoning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Cooks may soon be able to test
their ingredients for food-poisoning bacteria using a simple
kitchen appliance, Britain's New Scientist magazine reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
An experimental system developed by the Japanese company
Matsushita Electric, can now detect and measure the population of
pathogenic bacteria in a food sample in around 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
So far, it has successfully detected Salmonella strains and
Escherichia coli O157, but the researchers hope soon to modify the
test to also identify strains of Staphylococcus bacteria.
</P>
<P>
Matsushita believes that within two or three years it can build
an appliance small and cheap enough to use in a kitchen or
restaurant, allowing suspect food to be checked before serving.
</P>
<P>
According to Matsushita, the test requires no special skill and
is "as easy to do as a pregnancy test", simply requiring a
solution of the food to be poured into a tank.
</P>
<P>
The target size for the bug-detecting kitchen gadget, which
will cost 1000 U.S. dollars, was to be about as big as "three
blenders in a row", a Matsushita spokesman was quoted by New
Scientist as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
