<HEADLINE> Iraq Asks U.N. Compensation for Spread of Animal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has demanded that the
U.N. compensate its citizens for their losses resulting from the
spread of diseases among livestock and poultry which led to the
shortage of red meat and dairies.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Agriculture Minister Abdil-Ilah Hamid said that during
the 1970s Iraq installed a strategic vaccination project capable
of producing 12 million doses annually for preventing animal
diseases.
</P>
<P>
Work in this regard was suspended due to the 1991 Gulf War and
most of the production, diagnosis, and operation equipment were
destroyed in 1996 by the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, said
Hameed, quoted by the official Iraqi News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Iraq wrote to the U.N. to obtain approval to use some of the
said equipment in examining vaccine samples, said the minister,
complaining that the U.N. approval came incomplete and late, which
led to the spread of animal diseases.
</P>
<P>
Hameed asked the U.N. to send experts to estimate the degree of
damage in the vaccination project.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi media have reported that more than 1 million heads of
cattle and sheep have died of various animal diseases so far this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
