<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Urges G7 to Review Belgrade's Truce Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
made an urgent appeal to top leaders of the Group of Seven
Wednesday not to reject the unilateral truce announced by Belgrade
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin called for handover of the rights to solve the Kosovo
issue from the hands of military-men to diplomats, in a letter
addressed to top leaders of the United States, France, Germany,
Britain, Italy, Canada and Japan.
</P>
<P>
He asked them to review the gesture without preconceived idea
and with a constructive view and make appropriate response later.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia announced Tuesday that it would cease its military
action against the Kosovo Liberation Army and conduct direct
dialogue with Kosovo Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova. This
proposal does not bear any pre-conditions, Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
The tragic situation in Yugoslavia is getting more and more
serious and dangerous and the refugee problem has turned out to be
a disaster, Yeltsin told the leaders.
</P>
<P>
He called for most urgent measures to halt the deterioration of
the situation and bring it back to the political track. Russia is
making efforts so far as it could to achieve this, said Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials from the Group of Eight -- G7 plus Russia --
are scheduled to meet in Germany on Thursday following a meeting
of Contact Group officials on Wednesday. The Contact Group on
Yugoslavia is composed of Russia and five NATO members -- Britain,
France, Germany, Italy and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
