<HEADLINE> Killers of S. Africa's Chris Hani Denied Amnesty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The two convicted killers of
South African Communist Party leader Chris Hani were denied
amnesty by the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC)
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The TRC's amnesty committee said in a statement that Janusz
Walus and Clive Derby-Lewis have failed to make a full disclosure
of the 1993 assassination.
</P>
<P>
They also failed to sufficiently prove political motivation for
the murder.
</P>
<P>
"It is common cause that the applicants were not acting on
their express authority or orders from the Conservative Party (CP)
which they purport to represent in assassinating Mr. Hani.
</P>
<P>
"The CP has never adopted, propagated or espoused a policy of
violence or assassination of political opponents," the committee
said.
</P>
<P>
Derby-Lewis was formerly a member of parliament for the CP.
</P>
<P>
The committee also rejected Walus' claim that he had acted on
Derby- Lewis' orders.
</P>
<P>
Walus, with Derby-Lewis' help, shot and killed Hani in the
driveway of his home in Boksburg near Johannesburg, on April 10,
1993.
</P>
<P>
The South African Communist Party (SACP) immediately welcomed
the TRC decision.
</P>
<P>
SACP Deputy General Secretary Jeremy Cronin said the two men
have been evasive and often arrogant, and that the party is
convinced they have failed to meet any of the criteria for
amnesty.
</P>
<P>
Cronin said both men had been sentenced to death when they were
 convicted of Hani's murder. They could count themselves extremely
lucky that they are living under an African National Congress
government which has abolished the death penalty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
