<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Delegate: Dialogue Helps to Narrow Differenc es  on Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has all
along maintained that different opinions on human rights should be
solved through dialogue and exchanges on the basis of equality and
mutual respect, said a Chinese delegate here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"This has been proven the most effective way," said Ambassador
Qiao Zonghui, head of the Chinese delegation, at a meeting of the
ongoing 55th session of the United Nations Commission on Human
Rights.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has noted with appreciation that the
European Union (EU) has decided, for the second time, not to
sponsor a China resolution at the current commission session, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"This is a sensible move not only for the China-EU human rights
dialogue but also for defusing the confrontation in the
commission," he added.
</P>
<P>
However, Qiao said, the United States government announced on
March 26 that it would sponsor an anti-China resolution by itself
due to the so-called "sharp deterioration of China's human rights
record".
</P>
<P>
"The United States has unleashed attacks on China for trying
several criminals," he said. "And what I would like to make clear
is that these persons were arrested and tried for having engaged
in the activities subverting the state power and endangering state
security, which had nothing to do with their exercise of the
freedom of expression and association."
</P>
<P>
"It is a common practice of all countries including the United
States to punish criminals who have endangered state security," he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
According to the International Covenant on Economic, Social and
Cultural Rights and the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights, Qiao told the session, the exercise of rights is
not unlimited.
</P>
<P>
"Instead, it is subject to due limitations in the interests of
state security, public safety, public order and the rights and
freedoms of others," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qiao predicted that the U.S.-sponsored anti-China resolution
will be doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the anti-China resolution was defeated for seven
times demonstrates that confrontation leads to nowhere," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
