<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typing While Telephoning May Damage People's Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Making a telephone call while
typing on a computer, a condition known as "phone neck", can
damage people's health, British scientists have found.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at Surrey University, England, found that half of
all office workers investigated who use phone and computer
simultaneously for at least two hours a day suffer from neck pain.
</P>
<P>
The study, first of its kind in the UK, showed that almost a
third also have lower back pain and two thirds frequently or
sometimes experience headaches.
</P>
<P>
"Phone neck", caused by the phone being clasped between neck
and shoulder to free both hands for typing or taking notes, can
lead to degeneration of joints, inflammation of tendons, painful
muscle stiffening and disc trouble, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
It "increases the risk of nerve compression in the neck and
shoulder area, which could lead to problems in the spine, arm and
hands," said Elizabeth Simpson, a physiotherapist who led the
research.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Urged to Improve Roads for Relief Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The road condition in Kaputa area,
Northern Province of Zambia, remains the most pressing concern for
the agencies involved in the refugee relief effort, the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A report released by UNHCR Emergency Response Team in Kaputa
said a culvert bridge near Mununga along the Nchelenge Kaputa road
was partially washed away due to rising water levels and caused
delays in delivering a consignment of 54 tons of maize meal to
Kaputa.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR advised that incidents of refugees looting
agricultural fields in Kaputa as a result of delayed food
distributions have been isolated and should not be dramatized
since tensions between local residents and the refugees have been
minimal.
</P>
<P>
"We should not forget that more than 6,000 Congolese refugees
are still accommodated in the surrounding villages by family
members and this is a true example of Zambian generosity," said
the report.
</P>
<P>
The number of refugees in Kaputa town had risen to 17,467 by
Tuesday, it said. In addition, another 6,000 Congolese refugees
are estimated to reside in surrounding villages. The influx of
refugees from the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) continues at
a rate of about 200 new arrivals entering Zambia every day, it
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
