<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng's Visit to Further Sino-Pak Ties: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Information Minister
Mushahid Hussain said here Wednesday the forthcoming visit by
senior Chinese leader Li Peng is "extremely important" and will
further cement the existing friendly Sino-Pak ties.
</P>
<P>
The visit by Pi Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC) of China, will further push the
"new solid and substantive" relations between Pakistan and China
towards the 21st century, said Mushahid at a luncheon in honor of
Islamabad-based Chinese correspondents.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Speaker of Pakistan's National Assembly
Ellahi Bukhsh Soomro, Li Peng will make a five-day official,
goodwill visit to Pakistan starting Thursday. He will be the most
senior Chinese leader coming to Pakistan since Chinese President
Jiang Zemin's visit here at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Mushahid said Pakistan and China enjoy long-standing ties of
friendship underpinned by mutual trust and confidence and
sustained by the commonality of interest on regional and
international issues.
</P>
<P>
These ties, based on principles, have remained steadfast over
the decades, he said.
</P>
<P>
In spite of new developments in the regional and global
scenario, time-tested Sino-Pakistan relationship, based on
complete trust and understanding, has remained strong, vibrant and
important as ever to both sides, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Mushahid described Li Peng as "the old friend of Pakistan", as
he visited this South Asian nation 10 years ago in his capacity of
Chinese premier.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government, he said, attaches great importance to
the forthcoming visit by Li Peng. The visit will be an event of
great importance in the development of Pak-China bilateral
relationship, he added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion, Chinese Ambassador to Pakistan Lu
Shulin said that Li Peng's visit is "an important event" in
Sino-Pak relations, and it is especially important as the visit is
being made at the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese envoy termed the Sino-Pak relations as "profound,
time-tested, and all-weathered".
</P>
<P>
He expressed his belief that Li Peng's visit will further
strengthen the all-round partnership of cooperation between China
and Pakistan towards the new millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
