<HEADLINE> Pakistani Minister Projects Four Percent GDP Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Sounding optimism about the
future of the country's economy, Pakistani Finance Minister Ishaq
Dar Wednesday projected the economic growth rate at around four
percent for the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
The minister hoped that during the year 1998-99 "we will be
able to achieve a growth rate of around four percent with
inflation being contained below 7 percent and budgetary deficit
close to the budget estimates of 4.6 percent of Gross Domestic
Products (GDP)."
</P>
<P>
Dar was addressing a meeting here attended by the envoys of the
Pakistan Development Forum (PDF) member countries and heads of
international organizations and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
The PDF, previously known as Aid to Pakistan Consortium, is
scheduled to meet in Paris on April 22-23.
</P>
<P>
The minister's briefing was followed by a two-hour-long open
discussion on the present and future outlook of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Dar said he hopes that as a result of the efforts made by the
government, by the end of the current year or June, the economic
situation in his country will stabilize.
</P>
<P>
He also foresaw a GDP growth of 5.3 percent for the next fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
"This (growth rate) will be contributed mainly by agriculture
with 5.5 percent growth and manufacturing with 6.5 percent
growth," he added.
</P>
<P>
After resuming power by the Nawaz Sharif government in 1997,
the country managed to reverse the bad trend of economic
development in one year, said Dar.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the GDP grew by a mere 1.3 percent
in 1996-97 with a double-digit inflation rate, but a growth rate
of 5.4 percent was registered in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
In this background, he said, the fiscal year 1998-99 was
envisaged as a year of further consolidation of the gains achieved
during 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
But the sanctions Western countries imposed following the
nuclear tests last May and the worsening international economic
environment due to contagious financial crises around the world
posed serious difficulties to Pakistan's economy.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has pursued prudent and effective
policies to meet the new challenges, which has brought fairly good
results, according to Dar.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The situation has stabilized, economic growth is
reviving and business confidence restored. Positive signs are
visible all around."
</P>
<P>
However, the minister noted that difficulties on the economic
front are bound to have serious social consequences. "Despite low
inflation rate, increase in prices of some essential items has hit
the common man badly," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government is fully aware of these problems and have taken
a number of remedial measures in this regard, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
