<HEADLINE> Chinese Parliament Leader to Visit Pakistan Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC) of
China, will make a five-day official, goodwill visit to Pakistan
on April 8-12.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, who is coming here at the invitation of Ellahi Bukhsh
Soomro, speaker of Pakistan's National Assembly, is the most
senior Chinese leader to visit this South Asian nation since
Chinese President Jiang Zemin's visit here at the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng's visit forms an important part of the high-level
exchanges which are the hallmark of the time-tested friendship
between the two friendly neighbors, a press release by the
National Assembly said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said that Pakistan and China attach great significance to
such close consultations which offer the two sides opportunities
to deepen mutual understanding and share perception on issues of
mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan and China enjoy an exemplary relationship. The
long-standing ties of friendship between the two countries are
underpinned by mutual trust and confidence," the press release
said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan considers its relationship with China of great
significance constituting the cornerstone of its foreign policy,"
it said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Li Peng will call on President Rafiq Tarar
and hold substantive talks with Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and
discuss mutual cooperation with Soomro and Chairman of the Senate
Wasim Sajjad.
</P>
<P>
His meeting with Sharif will focus on all aspects of bilateral
relations and areas of interest to both countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leader will also deliver a keynote address on
Chinese priorities in the current global and regional strategic
scenario.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz will also call on Li Peng and
exchange views with him on important international, regional and
bilateral issues.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng will be decorated with Nishan-e-Pakistan, an award in
recognition of the great contribution made by him to the cause of
promoting understanding, friendship and cooperation between the
two fraternal countries.
</P>
<P>
Besides the capital city of Islamabad, Li Peng will also visit
Lahore, Pakistan's second largest city.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leader is scheduled to leave Pakistan for
Bangladesh on April 12 to continue his six-nation tour abroad.
Pakistan is the fourth leg of his current visit. 
</P>
