<HEADLINE> Number of Old People to Increase: WHO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of old people in
developing countries is expected to increase by between 200 and
400 percent by the year 2025, an official of the World Health
Organization (WHO) said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is pertinent to note that the most rapid changes in
population structure are taking place in developing countries
where the population of elderly people are predicted to increase
by between 200 and 400 percent by the year 2025," WHO regional
director Ebrahim Samba said in a statement to mark World Health
Day which falls on today.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of Africans aged 60 years or more would have
 increased to about 10.2 million in 2025, more than four times
what it was in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The extended family system, which used to act as a traditional
welfare system, had begun to disintegrate as a result of
modernization and urbanization, he said.
</P>
<P>
Elderly people no longer receive the kind of care and attention
they used to enjoy under the extended family system, he said.
</P>
<P>
Samba said this was a major social problem which African
communities must resolve.
</P>
<P>
He said it was necessary for countries to conduct surveys and
develop data on the subject for planning purposes and to draw up
national plans for the welfare of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
"The countries also need to put in place or expand
community-based programs for their elderly citizens and give
special attention to their health care needs," Samba said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
