<HEADLINE> U.S. Pledges $9M to Tanzania for Post-bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The United States government
has pledged to provide 9.23 million U.S. dollars to assist
Tanzania to recover from the tragic bombing at the U.S. Embassy in
Dar es Salaam last August.
</P>
<P>
An agreement for the grant was signed in the Tanzanian capital
Wednesday between U.S. Ambassador Charles Stith and Tanzanian
Minister of Finance Daniel Yona.
</P>
<P>
Out of the grant, four million dollars have been in place while
the rest is still in the pipeline, said Stith.
</P>
<P>
The grant, channelled through the United States Agency for
International Development (USAID), will provide direct assistance
to the bombing victims, assist in rehabilitating damaged
infrastructure facilities and enhance Tanzania's capacity in
disaster preparedness, said the U.S. ambassador.
</P>
<P>
The terrorist bombing at the U.S. embassy in Dar es Salaam on
August 7, 1998 left seven people dead and more than 70 others
injured.
</P>
<P>
Following the incident, the U.S. government provided Tanzania
with medicine and medical equipment worth 90,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, the Tanzanian financial
minister said that eight months after the bomb blast, memories of
the shocking incident are still fresh in Tanzanian people's minds.
</P>
<P>
He said the Tanzanian government wishes to reaffirm its total
commitment to eradicating international terrorism wherever it will
manifest its ugly head.
</P>
<P>
The minister also reassures the U.S. ambassador that Tanzania
is committed to maintaining and promoting bilateral relations with
the U.S. and to developing strong economic and commercial ties
with it.
</P>
<P>
Stith said although terrorists succeeded in killing and
wounding innocent people, they did not succeed in their goal of
estranging the two nations and in fact the bilateral ties between
the two countries have never been stronger. 
</P>
</TEXT>
