<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libraries in Ecuador, Micronesia, Gambia Designated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Three libraries, located in
Ecuador, Micronesia and Gambia, have been designated United
Nations depository libraries, and territories which bring United
Nations documents and publications to users around the world, U.N.
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They are the Universidad San Francisco de Quito Library,
Ecuador, the Learning Resources Center of the College of
Micronesia in Palikir, the new capital of the Federated States of
Micronesia, and the Gambia National Library in Banjul, capital of
Gambia.
</P>
<P>
The Universidad San Francisco de Quito Library, set up in 1988,
is the second United Nations depository library to be designated
in Ecuador. It serves a faculty of 500 professors, as well as a
body of 2,200 students, and is also open to the general public,
logging an average of 32,500 users per month.
</P>
<P>
The library maintains a collection of more than 70,000 volumes
of books and 6,000 audiovisual items and subscribes up to 580
periodicals.
</P>
<P>
The Learning Resources Center is the largest library in the
Federated States of Micronesia and the first United Nations
depository library designated in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Center serves the faculty and students of the College of
Micronesia, the only collegiate level institution in the country.
Its collections comprise more than 30,000 volumes of books, 230
periodical subscriptions and approximately 700 videotapes and
420 16mm films.
</P>
<P>
The Gambia National Library was established by the British
Colonial Office in 1946. In 1962, it was incorporated into the
Gambian Government, and in 1985 acquired autonomy.
</P>
<P>
The library, which serves as both a public and a national
library, maintains a collection of more than 115,000 volumes of
books, 85 periodical subscriptions and a special collection of
Gambiana.
</P>
<P>
Since 1946, the Dag Hammarskjold Library at the United Nations
headquarters in New York, part of the Department of Public
Information, has arranged for the distribution of United Nations
documents and publications to users around the world through its
depository library system.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 373 United Nations depository libraries:
55 are located in Africa, 100 in Asia and the Pacific, 32 in
Eastern Europe, 84 in Western Europe, 48 in Latin America and the
Caribbean, and 54 in North America.
</P>
<P>
These libraries receive United Nations materials, with the
understanding that their collections will be maintained in good
working order and be available to the public free of charge.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Member States, as well as non-Members, are
entitled to one "free depository," usually national library in the
capital city. In addition, the national parliamentary library, if
open to the public, is also entitled to receive material free of
charge, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
The designation of depositories is carried out by the United
Nations Publications Board. The degree of development of the
requesting libraries and the overall geographic distribution of
depository libraries in the countries concerned are among the
criteria used. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-07 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemeni Vice-President Calls China Tour Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni Vice-President Abdo Rabo
Mansour Hadi described his recent visit to China as very
successful and excellent in all aspects.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua upon his arrival at Sanaa
International Airport from a week-long tour of China, Hadi
expressed hope that the relationship and cooperation between Yemen
and China will be further strengthened in the future.
</P>
<P>
"During the visit I met Chinese President Jiang Zemin,
Vice-President Hu Jintao and other senior leaders," Hadi said,
adding "We discussed the bilateral ties as well as regional and
international issues. Our views were identical on all issues."
</P>
<P>
Hadi noted that the visit was a completion to the last year
China visit of Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh to implement
what was agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed with the Chinese president on the strategic
relationship and principles between the two countries," he added
</P>
<P>
The Yemeni leader expressed admiration for the significant
changes that took place in China over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
"During my stay in China I took note of the Chinese experience
and reforms," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the prospects of cooperation between the two countries
in the economic areas particularly in the oil area, the Yemeni
vice-president said the two sides discussed the gas sales and
agreed on the general principles of the oil and gas exploration as
well as the exchanges between the Chinese and Yemeni enterprises.
</P>
<P>
More talks will be held by the two countries on this issue over
the coming months, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two sides "dealt with the issue of rehabilitating the
spinning and weaving plants in Aden and Sanaa (of Yemen) and
making use of the Chinese hi-tech expertise," he said.
</P>
<P>
On developing cooperation between Xinchen economic zone in
south China, and the Aden free zone of Yemen, he said "We
discussed the relationship between the two zones and the exchange
of cono strengthen cooperation in the fields
of industry and transport," he added.
</P>
<P>
During his tour of China, Hadi visited Beijing, Shanghai and
Xinchen as well as other Chinese cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
