<HEADLINE> Turkish President to Visit Macedonia, Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel is expected to visit Macedonia and Albania on Sunday
in a bid to provide humanitarian aid to Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry said in a statement Wednesday that
Demirel will visit the two countries to examine the plight of
the Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
Along with Demirel's visit, Foreign Minister Ismail Cem will
meet with his counterparts from the European Union (EU) and other
Balkan countries in Luxembourg on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cem is also likely to take part in NATO foreign ministers'
meeting in Brussels, Belgium on Monday, Foreign Ministry Spokesman
Sermet Atacanli said.
</P>
<P>
Demirel had earlier appointed Turkey's ambassador to Belgrade
Ahmet Acet as his special envoy for Kosovo and sent him to
Macedonia and Albania on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Acet will deliver Demirel's special message to the leaders of
the two countries and will prepare a special report about the
current developments in the region.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Anatolia News Agency reported here on Wednesday that
over 8,000 Kosovo refugees had arrived in Turkey since NATO
started air strikes against Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, a member state of NATO, supports the military
alliance's bombings in Yugoslavia to press Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic into allowing NATO forces to enter Kosovo to
police a peace deal that would give broad autonomy to ethnic
Albanians who make up 90 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
A total of 11 Turkish warplanes stationed in the NATO bases in
Italy, have joined the NATO air strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
