<HEADLINE> Egyptian Court Suspends Rule on Libyan Dissident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's supreme court Wednesday
ordered the temporary suspension of the execution of a verdict
over a missing Libyan dissident pending a formal decision on the
case in October.
</P>
<P>
The Cairo Court of Appeal ruled in February that the Interior
Ministry was negligent for failing to protect Mansour Kikhia, a
former Libyan foreign minister, who disappeared in November 1993
in Cairo after attending a meeting of the Arab Human Rights
Organization. Kikhia's fate is not known now.
</P>
<P>
The court also ordered the ministry to pay Kikhia's wife, Baha
el-Emary, 100,000 Egyptian pounds (29,400 U.S. dollars) in
compensation. The ministry appealed against the ruling in March.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and the Interior Ministry have denied any role in
Kikhia's disappearance.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Court of Cassation said in a statement Wednesday that
it will examine the appeal and a decision on the case will be made
in October.
</P>
<P>
El-Emary, who is now living in Washington, first filed the suit
before the South Cairo Primary Court, holding the Interior
Ministry responsible for the disappearance of her husband.
</P>
<P>
The primary court turned down the suit, citing lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
El-Emary later appealed to the Cairo Court of Appeal and sought
500,000 pounds (147,000 dollars) in damages. The appeal court
maintained that Kikhia was a prominent figure and the Interior
Ministry was responsible for his security when he was in Egypt.
</P>
</TEXT>
