<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Seeks Additional Relief for Kosovar Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World
Food Program (WFP) has appealed to donor nations for an additional
24.1 million U.S. dollars to save the lives of Kosovar refugees in
Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro, a U.N. spokesman said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard told a press conference this brings
the total cost of the WFP's on-goning relief operations in the
region to 46.3 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a separate news release, Catherine Bertini, WFP executive
director, Wednesday said, "Our donors have been extremely generous
with food, money and logistical support. Donor response to the WFP
appeal has been so swift that 80 percent of resources have already
been pledged."
</P>
<P>
"But we are not out of the woods yet as people continue pouring
out of Kosovo," she said. "We need donors to cover the remaining
20 percent. If the refugee outflow proves to be more than 650,000,
WFP will still need more resources."
</P>
<P>
"The short-term and long-term needs of the refugees are
urgent," she said. "We need these additional funds to avert a
deterioration of the nutritional status of refugees. Some of these
refugees have not had enough to eat since the war began inside
Kosovo more than a year ago. Children are particularly hungry and
vulnerable."
</P>
<P>
As the WFP launched its appeal, the coordination of
humanitarian relief food supplies in Albania for the refugees was
in full swing, with 80 percent of the refugees in northern Albania
receiving full rations and 100 percent receiving at least some
relief food.
</P>
<P>
A massive exodus of refugees were forced to leave Yugoslavia
for neighboring Albania and Macedonia after their country was
bombed by NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
