<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Urges Role of U.N., OSCE in Halting NATO Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov Thursday called for a role of the United Nations and the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) in
solving the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, the OSCE could not play an active role in the Balkans
if NATO continued its military strikes against Yugoslavia, Ivanov
told the press after meeting with OSCE Chairman Knut Vollebaek.
</P>
<P>
What is the most crucial at the moment is to stop NATO's
military operation. Only after NATO halted the bombing could the
concerned parties sit down to seek a settlement of the Balkan
issues including the humanitarian crisis, said Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
The Balkan conflict proved again that Europe need a security
structure which can prevent conflict like the one in the Balkans,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Vollebaek, also the foreign minister of Norway, a NATO member,
is the first NATO minister to visit Moscow since NATO staged
attacks on Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
Vollebaek said the humanitarian disaster in the Balkans could
only be solved by political means. The OSCE welcomes any proposal
which can help solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He arrived in Moscow Thursday after a trip to Albania and
Macedonia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
