<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Houghton: Chinese Youth Side Among Best in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, Southwestern China, April 8 (Xinhua) -- China's
English manager Bob Houghton claimed his under-21 side are among
the best in Asia and can see off any challenges in a bid to
qualify for the 2000 Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Houghton, who also coaches the national eleven, said at the
training camp here on Thursday that the Chinese youth team stands
at the same level with the continental powerhouses South Korea and
Japan--if it wouldn't be fair to say so for their national squad.
</P>
<P>
"As long as we bring out our true selves--whatever the
opponents--we have every chance to reach the Sydney Olympics," the
Englishman told the reporters.
</P>
<P>
Though he admitted South Korea has the most competitive youth
team across the continent, which can be proved by the fact that
they narrowly beat defending champions China 1-0 in the final to
grab the Dunhill Cup Under-21 tournament trophy earlier this year
in Vietnam, Houghton reckoned his young men do have some edges
over their old nemesis.
</P>
<P>
"We are as good as the South Koreans, or maybe better than them,
as far as the individual talents are concerned, " he said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to talk about other Asian threats ahead of China,
who are attempting to grab their only second entry to the Olympic
soccer after 1988, "I don't know very much about the Japanese
Under-21 side, but from the performances of their youth team (in
the Nigerian World Youth Championship) I concluded it's a very
promising side."
</P>
<P>
As for Iran, which was reported to be dragged into a brawl
between coach and players, Houghton said they are no stronger than
the Chinese lads. The same with Saudi Arabia and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Houghton said he would mostly stick with the side which broke
into the last four at last year's Asian Games soccer tournament
when announcing the final 18-man list earlier May.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Olympic qualifying campaign begins on May 20 in
Hanoi, where China will take on the host side, Burma and the
People's Democratic Republic of Korea in the group stage.
</P>
<P>
The second leg of the round robin matches will be held in
Shanghai, China in June, with the best team to join eight other
top sides in a knock-out tournament to decide three Asian
representatives to Sydney. 
</P>
</TEXT>
