<HEADLINE> Russian Politicians Urge End to NATO Airstrikes on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Former Russian prime minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin, who is now Chairman of the "Russia is Our
Home," said on Thursday that Russia should make efforts to stop
NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
Chernomyrdin expressed his worry over the extension of the
Yugoslav crisis to other countries. Russia should manage to bring
both NATO and Yugoslavia to the negotiation table to avoid further
bleeding, he said while urging all politicians to unite together
for resolution of the Balkan crisis.
</P>
<P>
Another prominent Russian politician, Ruri Luzhkov, who serves
as the Mayor of Moscow and the Chairman of "Fatherland,"
reiterated on the same day that the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia
would not achieve any result.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if NATO sent its ground troops to Kosovo, it
would make another big mistake. By doing that, NATO would be
subject to "bushfighting" and face "the second Vietnam."
</P>
<P>
Luzhkov meanwhile called for an end to NATO airstrikes against
Yugoslavia, saying it had forced hundreds of thousands of Kosovo
Albanian refugees to flee their homes and widened the ethnic gap
in Kosovo. 
</P>
