<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Michael Chang Out of Hong Kong Open Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Hendrik Dreekmann of Germany
came from behind to knock out eighth seed Michael Chang of the
United States 3-6, 7-5, 6-4 at the second round of Salem Hong Kong
Open here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In other second round matches, veteran German player Boris
Becker defeated sixth seed Wayne Ferreira of South Africa in
straight sets while Andre Agassi of the United States, fifth seed
Nicolas Kiefer of Germany and seventh seed Jonas Bjorkman of
Sweden all advanced to the last eight.
</P>
<P>
Surprise winners of the first round, Germany's Bernd Karbacher
and Italy's Laurence Tieleman maintained their winning streak and
sailed through the next round.
</P>
<P>
Chang started his third clash with the 98th-ranked German
steadily and broke his third game to finish the first and drizzle-
interrupted set 6-3. But the German fought back immediately into
the second set by breaking Chang's first game with powerful serves
and blocks.
</P>
<P>
Chang broke back in the ninth game but wasted two break points
in the eleventh. Yet Dreekmann won one of the two break points in
the 12th game and leveled the set score at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
After the two served to 5-4 in the final set, Chang conceded
three break points in his fifth game and lost the match, which
lasted for 2 hours 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Chang said the defeat "hurt him a lot" and he was "taught to
win big points" since he missed some break points in the second
set. He added that he was not "tough enough" at the big points.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong favorite, who is to play in Japan Open next week,
said he hopes the Hong Kong Open will continue since Hong Kong is
a "great place and a special place" for him where he got "great
support".
</P>
<P>
Becker, who defeated Ferreira 6-4, 7-6 (12-10), said: "I still
go out there and do my best even I am semi-retired."
</P>
<P>
Becker said his first grand slam title was won at Wimbledon and
he hopes the last grand slam event he plays will also be a
Wimbledon, which is scheduled for coming June.
</P>
<P>
In the quarter-finals, Becker will play Tieleman, who
eliminated fourth seed Cedric Pioline of France in the first round
and knocked out Cecil Mamiit of the United States 6-3, 6-4 in the
second. Bjorkman will play Karbacher, who sent home second seed
Patrick Rafter of Australia in the first round and beat Brett
Steven of New Zealand in the second.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, beating Oliver Gross of Germany in straight sets, now
faces a tough battle with Kiefer, who scored an easy victory over
Paradorn Srichaphan of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, coming into the event with a wild card, said Kiefer is
"very tough on the whole court." 
</P>
</TEXT>
