<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finland to Grant 10 Million U.S. Dollars to Kosovo Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Finnish government on
Thursday pledged to provide an emergency aid of 55 million Finnish
markka (around 10 million U.S. dollars) to help Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
Of the money, 35 million Finnish markka (6.36 million U.S.
dollars) will be of humanitarian nature, and the remaining 20
million (3.64 million U.S. dollars) will be used to fund those
refugees stranded in neighboring Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
The government has said that it will take in some Kosovo
refugees but the number has yet to be decided. Meanwhile, the
Finnish Red Cross is to establish a makeshift hospital or two
clinics to give emergency medical treatment to refugees.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Finland is to take temporary measures to shelter
some refugees if the neighboring countries of Yugoslavia were
incapable of settling the numerous refugees who fled the flames of
war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
So far, the Finnish Red Cross has reportedly collected a
donation of 8.5 million Finnish markka (1.45 million U.S. dollars)
for Kosovo refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
