<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More SLA Militiamen Defect to Lebanese Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Another two members of the
Israeli-allied South Lebanon Army (SLA) defected to the Lebanese
army Thursday, three days after four militiamen turned themselves
in to the government.
</P>
<P>
The pair arrived at a Lebanese army checkpoint in the eastern
Bekaa Valley from Shebaa village in the eastern part of the
Israeli-occupied border zone in south Lebanon, the official
National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, four SLA members along with their wives and
children sneaked out of the 3,000-people village at dawn through
the hills and turned themselves in to the Lebanese army.
</P>
<P>
As a retaliation, Israeli forces Tuesday expelled 18 relatives
of the four defectors, mostly the elderly, children and women,
from the predominantly Sunni Muslim village.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government has delivered urgent messages to the
U.N., asking U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan to immediately
intervene and help the deportees go back to their homes.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-proclaimed security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the 2,500-member SLA is helping Israeli occupation
forces patrol the occupied zone and handling the security affairs
in Jezzine, a predominantly Christian town facing the enclave.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen were considered as traitors in Lebanon and SLA
commander Antonie Lahd has been sentenced to death in absentia by
a Lebanese military court.
</P>
<P>
Amid mounting speculation that Israeli forces may conduct a
unilateral partial withdrawal from south Lebanon, the SLA's moral
is sinking and more members are defecting to the Lebanese
government in a bid to escape a reprisal afterwards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
