Hangzhou Zhongchuang Corporation hosted a ceremony here today to
present 500 painted silk sets of the Analects of Confucius to the
organizing committee of the '99 International Horticultural
Exposition.
</P>
<P>
General Manager Zhou Rijian of the Hangzhou company noted that
the sets, the first collection of its kind produced in China, are
waterproof, borer-proof, anticorrosive and resistant to
ultraviolet rays.
</P>
<P>
The organizing committee will present the sets to foreign
guests attending the exposition which opens on May 1 this year,
according a committee official.
</P>
<P>
The total collection includes 1,550 English-Chinese copies and
1,000 Japanese-Chinese copies. Beijing University Professor Zhang
Dainian, a famous Confucian scholar and descendent of Confucius
Kong Demao wrote the preface for the collection.
</P>
<P>
Kong attended the ceremony and noted that this year will mark 2,
250th anniversary of the birth of Confucius. The 2,250 sets of the
collection were published to commemorate the great thinker.
</P>
<P>
She expressed hope that the collection will present the glamour
of traditional Chinese culture to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Wang Chong, deputy director of Yunnan Horticulture Bureau, said
preparatory work for the exposition is nearing completion. He
noted some 10 million people are expected to visit the
exposition's 10 exhibition halls and zones.
</P>
<P>
"The organizing committee has received numerous gifts from
throughout China, including replicas of two ornamental columns
from the Beijing municipal government and copper carriages from
Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
A special air route from Osaka to Kunming, capital of Yunnan
where the exposition will be staged, will accommodate the expected
surge of Japanese tourists, according to Wang.  
</P>
