<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. AIDS Program Gets Seventh Cosponsor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations International
Drug Control Program (UNDCP) has become the seventh cosponsor of
the Joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS (UNAIDS), announced
UNAIDS in a press release here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the importance of the joining of UNDCP to UNAIDS,
UNAIDS Executive Director Peter Piot said, "The use of
psychoactive drugs has facilitated the spread of HIV infection in
several ways. The most direct way is by HIV transmission through
needles shared by injecting drug users."
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, drug-induced loss of inhibitions can lead
to sexual and other high-risk behaviors that individuals might
otherwise avoid.
</P>
<P>
The UNDCP is active in supporting HIV/AIDS prevention programs
and including such components in its own programs to reduce the
demand for illicit drugs. Youth and groups engaging in high-risk
behavior are particularly targeted.
</P>
<P>
Coordination within the U.N. system has already resulted in
more effective programming responses to drug use and the AIDS
epidemic in a number of countries.
</P>
<P>
The six existing UNAIDS cosponsors are the United Nations
Children's Fund, the United Nations Development Program, the
United Nations Fund for Population Activities, United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization, the World
Health Organization and the World Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
