<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Reiterates Pledge Not to Get Involved in Balkan Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Thursday reiterated the pledge not to get involved militarily in
the Balkan crisis, saying that Russia would not provide weapons
for Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Providing arms for Yugoslavia would mean dragging Russia into a
world war, Yeltsin told Interfax before meeting with Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev. Yeltsin warned that it was in the Balkans
that the First World War erupted.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's statement came after a non-binding resolution passed
by the Lower House which called for military aid to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
NATO has expanded its range of bombing to civilian facilities.
The bombing was an unconscionable act, said Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting with Sergeyev, Yeltsin said that Russia
would make efforts to solve the Yugoslavia crisis by political and
diplomatic means and was preparing new initiatives for a peaceful
solution to the Yugoslav conflict.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev told the press after the meeting that the air raids
inflicted tremendous damage on Yugoslavia, yet they failed to
bring grave damage to the Yugoslav army. Yugoslavia still keeps
combat readiness.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev pointed out there were two ways in the development of
the situation in Yugoslavia. One was solving the problem
peacefully, while the other was building up military pressure by
launching ground war.
</P>
<P>
The second way would spread the conflict beyond the border of
Yugoslavia and make it turn out to be a protracted war, creating
more serious humanitarian disasters in the Balkans and resulting
in more causalities.
</P>
<P>
Russia's State Duma, or the lower house of parliament, voted
overwhelmingly on Wednesday for a resolution urging Yeltsin and
his government to provide military aid for Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Deputies in the house voted 279-34 for the non-binding
resolution, which also called for government delegations to visit
a number of countries, including Germany, France, Italy, Greece,
Romania, Bulgaria, India and Egypt, to explain Russia's opposition
to NATO military strikes on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The resolution urged the president and his government to
discuss and adopt necessary measures by April 15 for providing
weapons and spare parts for Yugoslavia and sending a military
delegation to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
