<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Human Rights Body Criticizes Forced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian human rights group on
Thursday criticized an Iranian revolutionary court for closing
down the moderate daily Zan (women) and called for investigation
based on the constitution and press law.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Hassan Ziaeifar, secretary general of the Islamic
Human Rights Commission (IHRC) which was set up in 1995, said that
to deal with any press offense in Iran, there is no way but to
observe the constitution and the press law.
</P>
<P>
He said that resorting to any other means in this regard will
result in deviation from the press law and tension in society, the
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper was banned for publishing a letter of Farah Diba, the
ousted Iranian queen, and a caricature making fun of "blood money"
-- money paid to the family of a murdered person as compensation
by the murderer. Paying ``blood money'' is one of the main
judicial and religious principles of Islam.
</P>
<P>
However, the daily's managing director Faezeh Hashemi on
Wednesday rejected the charges against her daily and accused the
closure as a "political move" by the conservatives against the
moderates, the main supporters of the reformist President Mohammad
Khatami.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Hashemi underlined that the
case of her daily should be investigated by the Ministry of
Culture and Islamic Guidance or the press court, not the
revolutionary court.
</P>
<P>
The ban on Zan can be seen as part of the campaigns by the
hard-line factions for the sixth Majlis (parliament) elections
slated early next year, said Hashemi, daughter of former Iranian
President Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance on
Wednesday night also expressed regret over the closure of Zan and
underlined that all press offenses should be dealt with by the
press court in open sessions and in the presence of a jury
according to the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Issuing a statement, the ministry called on the conservative
revolutionary court to respect freedom of writing and safeguard
press freedom.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that it has sent a written warning to the
daily's managing director deploring the negligence of the daily in
its publication.
</P>
<P>
Noting the possibility of making mistakes is unavoidable in
journalism, the ministry also called on the daily's managers to
clearly apologize for the mistake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
