Netanyahu said here on Thursday that Israel is considering taking
in more refugees from Kosovo, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said he has asked the Foreign Ministry to prepare for
the arrival of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night, Netanyahu announced Israel has decided to
take in 100 refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He said the refugees can stay in Israel for six months, after
which they can decide for themselves whether to remain in Israel
or leave.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Netanyahu stressed there is no gap in his and
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon's positions on the Kosovo crisis. He
said they both support NATO's actions against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said Sharon's remarks that an independent state in
Kosovo can only turn into an international base for Islamic
terrorist activities are only his personal assessment which do not
reflect the current Israeli policy.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli opposition Labor Party leader Ehud Barak accused
the government of speaking in two voices on the Kosovo crisis. He
said the government should take a clear stand in support of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's actions.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the Jewish Agency continued its
effort to aid the Kosovo refugees now stranded in Albania.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the agency sent the second plane to Albania which
carried seven tons of supplies.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that it will continue sending aid to Albania
every day until next Monday. 
