<HEADLINE> Poll: Majority Palestinians still Support Oslo Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Fifty-six percent of the
Palestinians gave their support to the Oslo Accords in a
Palestinian opinion poll released here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted by the Jerusalem Media and Communication
Center on March 18-19 among 1199 Palestinians in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, said 63.7 percent of the total respondents gave
their backing to the Palestinian-Israeli peace process, while 34.7
percent did not.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 69 percent of the respondents said they are
optimistic about the Palestinians' peace negotiations with Isarel
and 23.9 percent said they are pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
On the question of the performance of the Palestinian National
Authority, 62 percent term it as "good," while 35 percent gave an
negative answer. A total of 62.9 percent respondents said they
trust Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and 49.4 percent said
Arafat has done a very good job.
</P>
<P>
A total of 70.7 percent respondents said they support the
formation of a national unity government and 67.6 percent held
that there would be a good cooperation between Fatah and Hamas if
such a coalition is formed.
</P>
<P>
For the most important problems in the peace process the
palestinian people are facing, 46.2 percent said it is
"Jerusalem," followed by the issue of Jewish settlement (30.8
percent) and refugee issue (14.8 percent).
</P>
<P>
The majority of the respondents said they support the
establishment of an independent Palestinian state, with 79.8
percent saying they support a state to be run according to
the Islamic law.
</P>
<P>
On the question of "resumption of military actions against the
Israeli targets because of the lack of progress in the peace
process," 56 percent opposed such ideas while 35.7 percent said
"okay," and 66.5 percent strongly oppose any kind of "suicide
bombings."
</P>
<P>
Replying to the question of Israel's upcoming elections in
May, 50.2 percent said there will be no
difference whether Likud or Labor wins, while 24.5 percent
expected an improvement in the political situation if the Labor
comes to power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
