<HEADLINE> Indian President Urges Papers to Stop Commercializing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Indian President Kocheril Raman
Narayanan Thursday urged Indian newspapers to resist the tendency
of "trivializing and commercializing" news and contribute to
preservation of India's identity and culture.
</P>
<P>
"While competing with the electronic media, newspapers tend to
trivialize and commercialize news... It is an irresistible
tendency but has to be resisted," Narayanan said while addressing
a ceremony to mark the 50th anniversary of the founding of Indian
Newspaper Society.
</P>
<P>
He said that newspapers in India had become a "staple diet" of
the people and part and parcel of daily life and, therefore, they
should pass on cultural values.
</P>
<P>
The Indian president said that despite competing with the
exploding electronic media, the print media would have its
supremacy and described it as a "soul-stirring instrument unlike
the electronic media".
</P>
<P>
Newspapers would play a predominant role in the next
millennium, he said, adding that they were "closer to the people,
read the pulse of the people and purvey news that is acceptable to
the masses".
</P>
<P>
Latest figures show that over 39,000 newspapers and periodicals
are now published in India in as many as 100 languages and
dialects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
