cents to close at 9.35 Singapore dollars. Asean was less 20 cents
to end at 6.8 U.S. dollars. DBS, OCBC and UOB F lost 20 cents each
to finish at 10.5, 12.7 and 11.7 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said a strong buying trend dominated the market as the
stocks gained after four consecutive days and the market surged up
6.2 percent this week, supported by a heavy inflow of foreign
liquidity.
</P>
<P>
They said that even an announcement by Hong Kong's HKR Holding
that it would not purchase a stake in UIC has not slowed the
rush-in of foreign investment. 
