<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Records Lowest GDP Growth Rate in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The GDP growth rate for Nepal
hit an all-time low of 2.1 percent in 1998 as against 3.8 percent
in 1997, said the economic and social survey of Asia and the
Pacific 1999 released here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Other countries in the South Asian region recorded higher
estimated growth rates in 1998 with 5.6 percent for Bangladesh,
5.0 percent for Bhutan, 6.0 percent for India, 5.4 percent for
Pakistan and 5.5 percent for Sri Lanka, said the survey conducted
by the United Nations Economic and Social Commission for Asia and
the Pacific (ESCAP).
</P>
<P>
The survey found that as a result of bad weather, agriculture,
which contributes to about 40 percent of GDP in Nepal, grew by
only 1.1 percent in 1998 compared with 4.1 percent in 1997 while
non-agricultural sector grew by 2.8 percent, down from 3.5 percent
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Growth in the manufacturing sector in Nepal declined as well
because of a downturn in the carpet and ready-made garment
industries but the service sector performed better as tourist
arrivals improved in the Visit Nepal Year '98, the survey noted.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rate in Nepal fell to 4.0 percent in 1998 from 7.7
percent in 1997. As a result, lower growth in prices of food and
non-food items was observed.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that in 1998 Nepal's exports to India, its
biggest trading partner, increased by more than 50 percent; total
merchandise exports grew by 11.7 percent which was slightly higher
than 1997.
</P>
<P>
Imports from India increased marginally whereas imports from
other countries fell sharply. The survey noted that trade deficit
decreased substantially for Nepal in 1998 as a result of good
exports and fall in imports.
</P>
<P>
For increasing liquidity to boost the economy, nominal
refinance rate was lowered, maturity restrictions on government
securities and re-discounting and secondary transaction were
removed and cash reserve ratio was lowered in 1998 in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, foreign direct investment in Nepal decreased to 11.1
million U.S. dollars as against 28.4 million dollars in 1997.
However, there was a large increase in foreign aid and overall
balance of payments was in surplus, the survey noted.
</P>
<P>
It said foreign investment has been welcomed in Nepal, but
delayed structural reforms, often due to political instability,
constrained such investment.
</P>
<P>
The issue of large sums of non-performing loans continues to
create concern and the need to create an enabling environment for
the private sector has been increasingly recognized, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
