<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pact Reached Over Currency Issue in Somalia + </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 8 (Xinhua) -- An agreement was reached between
faction leader Hussein Aidid and the businessmen in south
Mogadishu Thursday over the disputed importation of newly printed
Somali shilling notes.
</P>
<P>
In a joint press conference held by Aidid and Mohamed Abdulle
Daylaf, who spoke on behalf of the businessmen, the two sides
announced what they called a total settlement over their five-day
dispute.
</P>
<P>
But neither side went into the details to mention the terms of
their agreement.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, sources close to the businessmen said that Aidid
has renounced his claim of having the rights to control the money,
while the businessmen themselves had come up with a compromising
agenda acknowledging the existence of Aidid's authority as their
faction leader since they both belong to the same Habar Gidir
clan.
</P>
<P>
Since the dispute has been settled, more than 35 billion Somali
 shillings worth of four million U.S. dollars are expected to soon
reach Ballidogle airport, 90 kilometers south of Mogadishu, as the
first consignment.
</P>
<P>
About 50 battle wagons and nearly 700 heavily-armed militiamen
belonging to the businessmen are now stretched between Mogadishu
and Ballidogle airport, ready to escort and secure the arrival of
the money.
</P>
<P>
If successful, the rest of 100 billion Somali shilling notes
will follow to reach Mogadishu later on. This will make the total
amount of the notes worth 14 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The release of the money printed in Canada by a Malaysian group
 known as Adorna has been worked out smoothly by the businessmen
after allegedly paying 800,000 dollars more for the completion of
its printing.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian Adorna group had in 1996 agreed with late General
Aidid to print over 170 billion somali shilling notes for his
faction.
</P>
<P>
However, the first consignment of the money of 35 billion
Somali shillings worth of four million dollars, had reached
Mogadishu in 1997 and was used by Hussein Aidid's faction.
</P>
<P>
The value of the Somali shillings against the hard currencies
especially the U.S. dollar has taken a new low in its history as
the news of the agreement between Aidid and the independent
businessmen over the money dispute has reached the streets and the
capital markets. One dollar Thursday can buy 9,000 Somali
shillings instead of 8,560 shillings in late March.
</P>
<P>
According to the economists, the printing of the Somali
shilling notes will be an open business for all, thus further
endangering the overall poor economy and the existence of the
Somali shillings as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Some businessmen have already begun selling their goods only in
U.S. dollars, predicting that the value of Somali shilling will
keep devaluating.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
