<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian, Pacific Region Economy Recovering: UN Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A UN report released here on
Thursday says that the economic crisis in Asia may have bottomed
out and the regional economy may start a stable recovery soon.
</P>
<P>
The Economic and Social Survey of Asia and the Pacific 1999, an
annual investigation conducted by the Economic and Social Council
for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP), a part of the United Nations,
concludes that although uncertainties remain in the near future,
evidence of recovery has begun to show up.
</P>
<P>
Trade surplus and foreign exchange reserves have all began to
pick up in some of the nations that had been severely hit by the
economic crisis. Foreign exchange rates and stock markets have
also shown signs of recovery while the pressure of inflation has
been eased, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Although the economic prospects remain not very clear, the
report says that it is generally agreed that the worst period of
the crisis has gone away and that the economy of Asia and the
Pacific region may soon pick up.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of gross domestic product (GDP) of the
developing nations in the region is expected to increase from 0.2
percent in 1998 to 3.6 percent in 1999, the report says. The GDP
of southeast Asian nations is expected to rise from a negative 6.2
percent to 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Due to the worsening of the Asian financial crisis,
international trade and economic growth in the region dropped
significantly last year from the previous year. Among the 19
countries on the Asian continent, seven reported a negative
economic growth last year.
</P>
<P>
China's GDP growth rate declined one percentage point to 7.8
percent last year, but it was still one of the highest in the
world, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
