<HEADLINE> Arafat Hints At Delaying Independence Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, on
a visit to Japan, on Thursday hinted at delaying a planned
unilateral declaration of independence by Palestine, the Kyodo
News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat expressed the intention during a meeting with Japanese
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, Kyodo quoted a Japanese Foreign
Ministry official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to make a final decision that will satisfy all the
nations, including Japan...that advised me to postpone the
declaration at least until Israel holds a general election (May 17)
," Arafat told Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Tokyo Wednesday for a two-day visit. In his
talks Wednesday evening with Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko
Komura, Arafat spelled out his plan to make a final decision
around April 27 when the Palestinian Central Council convenes to
discuss the planned statehood.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi advised Arafat to delay his plan to unilaterally declare
an independent Palestinian state on May 5, the day after an
interim self-rule agreement with Israel expires, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi, however, reiterated Japan's support for the right of
Palestinians to self-determination, and vowed to continue "both
economic and political assistance" to help Palestinians build a
state through the peace process with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The five-year interim accord cleared the way for negotiations
to begin on a final, comprehensive peace settlement as called for
in the 1993 Oslo accord.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has been traveling around the world to listen to
opinions about his plan to declare statehood.
</P>
<P>
He visited Turkey, Jordan and Russia before flying into Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
After ending his visit to Japan on Thursday, Arafat left for
Vietnam and will later visit China, Indonesia, Pakistan and other
Asian nations as well as African nations. He has already traveled
to European nations and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
