<HEADLINE> Rwanda Genocide Never Committed Again: OAU Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Salim Ahmed Salim, Secretary
General of the Organization of African Unity (OAU), reaffirmed the
resolve to ensure that Rwanda genocide is never committed again in
the African Continent or any where else in the world, local
newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made Wednesday by the OAU Secretary General
when he was speaking at a meeting here to commemorate the fifth
anniversary of Rwanda genocide which killed over 500,000 Rwandan
from April to July 1994.
</P>
<P>
Salim said, "this ghastly event will forever haunt us and evoke
the indictment to our collective humanity as we recalled how the
world watched with horror but did very little, if anything at all,
to stop the brutal and systematic decimation of a people."
</P>
<P>
He recalled the endorsement of the establishment of an
international panel of eminent personalities to investigate the
genocide in Rwanda and the events surrounding it in the Great
Lakes region by the Assembly of Heads of State and Government
meeting in Ouagadougou in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the main objective of the panel is to draw
a lesson from the Rwandan tragedy and to contribute toward the
promotion of national healing, reconciliation and cohesion in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion, K.Y. Amoako, Executive Secretary of
the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), said the
most fundamental cause of civil conflict in Africa is not ethnic
diversity but poverty which is also a consequence of civil war.
</P>
<P>
He urged the international community to support the people and
government of Rwanda in their efforts for reconciliation and
economic growth "necessary to address the poverty and economic
inequities, as well as other social and political underpinnings of
the conflict". 
</P>
</TEXT>
