<HEADLINE> China to Legislate for Small, Medium-Sized Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A law drafting team for the law on
the promotion of small and medium-sized enterprises was installed
here today under a National People's Congress subcommittee, the
Financial and Economic Committee.
</P>
<P>
Small and medium-sized enterprises are an important component
of China's national economy but are in a disadvantageous position
compared with their larger competitors, senior legislators and
government officials said at today's installation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Legislation to promote the development and competence of small
and medium-sized enterprises is necessary for national economic
development and reform of the country's economic system, said Chen
Guangyi, chairman of the NPC Financial and Economic Committee.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the number of small and
medium-sized enterprises registered with the government now
exceeds 10 million.
</P>
<P>
These enterprises produce 60 percent of the total value of
industrial output, contribute 40 percent of all taxes and profits,
and provide 75 percent of all urban jobs, said Shi Wanpeng, vice
minister of the State Commission of Economy and Trade.
</P>
<P>
According to legislators, a draft law based on opinions
solicited nationwide is expected to be submitted for discussion by
the NPC Financial and Economic Committee in 2001.  
</P>
</TEXT>
