<HEADLINE> Nigerian Youths Hold 13 Oil Stations over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Angry youths in the Niger Delta of
Nigeria took a new dimension Wednesday when youths from 61 Ijaw
communities took over 13 flow stations demanding more compensation
by oil companies for their oil spills.
</P>
<P>
After the expiration of an ultimatum Monday, the youths have
already seized five barges, four tugboats and one sea track
belonging to oil companies in the region, This Day newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a release issued by the Association of Mobil Spill Affected
Communities (AMSAC), the youths said that they had rounded up its
war against Mobil Producing Nigeria Unlimited with the taking over
of 13 flow stations Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, seven flow stations belong to Shell
in the Batan area and six in the North Bank Oil Fields belong to
Agip.
</P>
<P>
AMSAC's dispute with Mobil started after the 40,000 barrels
spill at Idoho Oit on January 12, 1998 which affected members of
AMSAC communities and other settlements along the Atlantic
Coastline.
</P>
<P>
After paying 20,000 naira (about 222 U.S. dollars) to some
victims, Mobil is said to have refused to pay the rest of the two
billion (about 22 million Dollars) naira compensation demanded by
the affected communities.
</P>
<P>
The youths said that they are ready to "meet force with force
in case any military enforcement is sent to the area." 
