<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Caohai Lake, Home to 100,000 Migratory Birds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Caohai Lake, a freshwater lake in
southwest China's Guizhou Province, has attracted many overseas
and local visitors with its 100,000 migratory birds including 400
endangered black-neck cranes and grey cranes.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Honglin, an official from the Caohai State-
Level Nature Reserve, there are 27 varieties of state-protected
birds now living on the lake, which covers 96 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Local people and the migrants birds are friendly to each other.
"Once I took picture of a bird only three meters away," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Local villagers have been urged to love and protect these birds
of passage, and in recent, with the help of several international
organizations, local governments have integrated poverty-relief
work with efforts to protect the birds. 
</P>
