<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asia Records Exceptional GDP Growth: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 8 (Xinhua) -- South Asia was the only bright
exception in 1998 when developing economies in the Economic and
Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) region as a
group recorded a growth rate of close to zero percent due to
deepening financial crisis, a survey on the region found.
</P>
<P>
South and Southwest Asia recorded an estimated 5.3 percent
growth of real GDP in 1998 while the developing economies as a
whole in the region witnessed a growth rate of only 0.2 percent as
against over 7 percent in 1996 and almost 6 percent in 1997, noted
the economic and social survey released here Thursday by the
ESCAP, a U.N. commission.
</P>
<P>
In the South Asian region, the real GDP growth rate in 1998 was
5.6 percent, 5.0 percent, 6.0 percent, 2.1 percent, 5.4 percent
and 5.5 percent respectively for Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Nepal,
Pakistan and Sri Lanka when major developing economies in other
sub-regions saw negative growth rates.
</P>
<P>
The real GDP growth rate for the developed economies of the
ESCAP region was minus 2.2 percent in 1998, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that after a growth rate of 3.2 percent in 1997, the
world economy slowed sharply to a rate of 1.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Inflation rates in the countries of South and Southwest Asia
were either lower, or increased very slightly in 1998 as compared
with 1997, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
In the sub-region, the relative insulation of the financial
markets moderated the contagion effect of the regional economic
crisis on the domestic economy, the survey observed.
</P>
<P>
Among the least developed countries, growth was much less
robust in Southeast Asia than in South Asia. The survey said one
reason was that foreign direct investment flows to these countries
slowed as investors from Malaysia, Singapore and Thailand either
delayed or canceled proposed projects.
</P>
<P>
However, the slowness in achieving greater depth in financial
markets has been an impediment in diversifying the sources of
finance for development in the South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The achievement of higher GDP growth rates has also been
constrained by inadequate infrastructure, low productivity and
inefficiency in public sector enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"Fiscal improvement is another issue with which most of the
countries of the South and Southwest Asian regions have been
grappling with little success," the survey noted.
</P>
<P>
It said for the least developed countries, namely, Bangladesh,
Bhutan, the Maldives and Nepal in the South Asian region, poverty
alleviation continues to be the major challenge.
</P>
<P>
"To break through the poverty syndrome, the existing pace of
GDP growth needs to be accelerated significantly," it said. "A
pertinent policy issue for these countries is how the quality and
effectiveness of official development assistance, on which they
are dependent, can be enhanced."
</P>
<P>
The survey for 1999 also touched upon the application of
information and communication technology.
</P>
<P>
It said much more progress in making the technology accessible
to economic actors has occurred in the newly industrializing
economies and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
countries, and in some other larger countries including China and
India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
