<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Announces Strategy to Build Technopreneurship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Deputy Prime Minister
and Minister for Defense Tony Tan Keng Yam Thursday announced his
country's comprehensive strategy to build a critical mass of
technopreneurial talent.
</P>
<P>
Tony Tan, who chairs the Technopreneurship 21 Ministerial
Committee, told a press conference that Singapore will launch a
systematic, comprehensive strategic plan to develop and attract
technopreneurship talent to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
In outlining the strategy, he said it will be carried out
through four initiatives centering on education, facilities,
regulations and financing.
</P>
<P>
Citing education as a crucial component of the strategic plan,
Tony Tan said Singapore universities should be revised to become
engines of innovation and technopreneurship and grow into world
class institutions which are not only generators of trained
manpower but also generators of business opportunity.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that Singaporeans need to be infused with a culture
of innovation and enterprise and a readiness to take calculated
risks through education, he said, "We have started revamping our
schools to encourage innovation and creative thinking and
pervasively use and exploit information technology," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tony Tan said comfortable and conducive facilities that provide
an intellectually stimulating and creative environment will be
created under the so-called T21 plan to attract technopreneurial
talent to gather.
</P>
<P>
He also said a review of rules and regulations will be made
with the aim of removing obstacles and building up a more
supportive environment and infrastructure for technopreneurs to
start business and realize their full potential.
</P>
<P>
"We will change our laws and regulations if recommended and
found necessary," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the deputy prime minister, the Singapore
government will establish a 1-billion-U.S.-dollar
Technopreneurship Investment Fund (TIF) to signal its commitment
to technopreneurship development.
</P>
<P>
The TIF is intended to draw more venture capital activities
into Singapore, Tony Tan added.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the National Science and Technology
Board will be designated as the leading government agency to
provide focus and direction to the technopreneurship drive.
</P>
<P>
Tony Tan said the most important challenge for the Singapore
economy in the 21st century is to rapidly transit from a
capital-intensive manufacturing and services economy to a globally
competitive advanced knowledge economy with a strong and vibrant
technopreneurship sector within the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Innovation and technopreneurship will form a crucial part of
Singapore's next wave of economic growth in the 21st century, he
said, stressing that it is the earlier the better to promote
technopreneurship. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Media Giant Drives Stocks to Record Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket surged
to another all-time closing high Thursday, powered by a bullish
performance in select blue chip stocks, in particular Rupert
Murdoch's News Corp.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries Index ended 26.6 points stronger
at 3,056.2 after hitting a record intraday high of 3,061.6 points.
</P>
<P>
It eclipsed the previous record closing high of 3032.9 set on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The continuation of the recent strength in the market was
driven again by News Corp. with the Commonwealth Bank and Rio
Tinto also leaping ahead, while the broader market was marginally
better, Shaw Stockbroking dealer Jamie Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
The market also showed a trend to stay above the 3,000-point
mark.
</P>
<P>
"Probably domestically the catalyst to holding it above 3,000
would be if interest rates do flatten out and could potentially go
lower from here," Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
News Corp.'s ordinary shares closed 71 cents, or 5.25 percent,
firmer. Volume was a massive 8.31 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The group's preferred shares were 67.5 cents, or 5.28 percent,
higher at 13.46 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Overall the media sector performed strongly, with Publishing
and Broadcasting climbing 41 cents, or 4.2 percent on speculation
that the media company would bring forward plans to float its
on-line business.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Ten Network Holdings climbed 7 cents, after it posted
solid first-half earnings Wednesday, while Seven Network shares
were flat at 5.25 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth and ANZ banks also provided some spark to the
banking sector, rising 48.6 cents and 25.5 cents respectively.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank closed 5 cents higher while Westpac
dropped 1.3 cents.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the All Industrials Index rose 52.9 points to 5,516.6
while the All Resources Index added 3.4 points to 1,037.6.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of the resources sector was Rio Tinto, which
jumped 73 cents, or 3.37 percent, after a rise in London Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
But the rise failed to help fellow miners WMC which lost 3.7
cents at the end of the day and North, which was down 1.2 cents.
Sector leader BHP added 2 cents.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 8.4 points to 960.3.
</P>
<P>
In Sydney gold bullion closed at 280.15 U.S. dollars an ounce,
a rise of 1.15 dollars an ounce from Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
National turnover stood at 460.71 million shares worth 1.31
billion Australian dollars (816.13 million U.S. dollars). There
were 605 falling stocks and 564 rising ones while 450 remained
steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
