<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise For Fourth Straight Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices surged in Tokyo for the
fourth consecutive trading day Thursday, boosted by continued
brisk buying by foreign investors and a strong showing Wednesday
on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 292.19 points, or 1.77
percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 16,846.69, finishing
above 16,800 for the first time since March 26 last year.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, advanced 20.43 points, or 1.54 percent to 1,
345.07.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section expanded to 826.47 million shares
from 709.71 million shares Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei opened lower, dragged down by selling following the
recent gains. It soon rebounded, however, helped by the rise in
New York stock prices and the U.S. dollar's strength against the
yen, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors have played the major role in lifting share
prices in Tokyo, and their active stance has encouraged those who
waited to buy stocks on dips to move in, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers outnumbered
losers 882 to 351, with 95 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
