<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Weakens With Fall in Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Weaker-than-expected labor force
figures pushed the already tenuous Australian dollar down almost
three quarters of a U.S. cent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The local currency finished at 62.36 U.S. cents, its lowest
level in more than a month. It closed at 63.06 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Rothschild &AMP; Sons senior foreign exchange manager Paul
Macarounas said that selling interest in the Australian dollar had
been evident during the morning and the jobs figures from the
Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) simply tipped it over.
</P>
<P>
Macarounas said earlier in the week the Australian dollar was
stubbornly holding onto the 63.00 U.S. cents level.
</P>
<P>
"And really it should have been lower, especially with the U.S.
dollar/Japanese yen exchange rate breaking higher and gold
languishing around its lows," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Today it had a little bit of a catch up, certainly the numbers
have helped but really the selling started before the figures came
out," he added.
</P>
<P>
The ABS reported total employment fell by 7,400 to 8.703
million, adjusted, in March after rising by 32,900 in February.
</P>
<P>
Australia's unemployment rate remained steady at 7.4 percent
and the participation rate was at 63.0 percent from 63.1 percent
in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate had been expected to rise to 7.5 percent
with forecasts ranging between 7.3 percent and 7.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The worse than expected employment numbers pushed it through
62.50 U.S. cents," Macarounas said.
</P>
<P>
On the cross rates, the Australian dollar was buying 0.5777
euro from 0.5831 at Wednesday's close and 75.40 Japanese yen from
76.24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 09:47 </DATE_TIME>
