<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharon to Demand Russia Halt Technology Transfer to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel
Sharon will make a visit to Russia next week during which he will
ask for a halt to Russia's alleged transfer of nuclear technology
to Iran, Israel Radio reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The visit will be Sharon's third trip to Moscow in less than a
month, during which he will meet with his Russian counterpart Igor
Ivanov also over improving the relationship between Israel and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Sharon's scheduled visit to Moscow was announced after he
expressed his reservations about the ongoing airstrikes on
Yugoslavia by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
Sharon has avoided condemning Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and has not voiced support for the NATO strike.
</P>
<P>
In response, the Russian Foreign Ministry has expressed
"satisfaction" with Sharon's position, officials in Israeli Prime
Minister's Office disclosed.
</P>
<P>
A source in the Israeli government told local daily Haaretz
that Sharon's lukewarm approach to NATO's actions in Yugoslavia
was driven by a desire to woo the Russians, the traditional ally
of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
"Sharon believes that such a position on Kosovo will enable
him to get something in return from the Russians in two
spheres: the halting of the transfer of technology to Iran and
the generation of economic links, such as investments," the
source said.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said it has evidence that Russian firms are
providing nuclear weapons technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
However, Russia insists that all its government agencies are
in compliance with rules designed to prevent the spread of
nuclear technology.
</P>
<P>
There has been no breakthrough on the issue during Sharon's
visits to Moscow last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 09:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Cabinet Approves 1999 Budget Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese cabinet Wednesday
night endorsed the 1999 fiscal budget bill which sets the deficit
at 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bill will be submitted to the parliament for approval.
</P>
<P>
The bill targets revenue for 1999 at 4,990 billion Lebanese
pounds (3.32 billion U.S. dollars), compared with 4,430 billion
pounds (2.95 billion dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The spending was set at 8360 billion Lebanese pounds (about 5.5
billion dollars), compared with 7,186 billion pounds (4.79 billion
dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Information Minister Anwar Khalil told reporters after
the cabinet session on Wednesday night that a new income tax
system would be imposed, replacing the existing flat rate of 10
percent. But, he didn't give any details of the system.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star Thursday quoted cabinet sources as saying the
government would introduce a 30 percent tax on alcoholic
beverages, tobacco and other non-essential commodities and increase
gasoline price by 2,000 pounds (1.3 dollars) per 20 liters.
</P>
<P>
However, customs duties on raw materials for industry were
lowered on a range of goods.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also decided to impose a 40 percent price hike on
celluar telephone calls, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese economy is undergoing a record recession since the end
of the 1975-1990 civil war with the public debts having hit 18
billion U.S. dollars, one of the highest in the world on per
capita basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: "No Position" on Cypriot Mediation Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States declined to take
a position on a Cypriot initiative for the release of three U.S.
soldiers captured by Yugoslav forces, the Cyprus News Agency
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Our Ambassador in Greece and our Embassy in Cyprus are talking
to the relevant governments and we have been informed of their
intentions and we are not going to take a position on this,"
U.S. State Department Spokesman James Rubin told the press.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' House of Representatives (parliament) Speaker Spyros
Kyprianou flew to Athens on Wednesday and is waiting for a safe
passage later Thursday to Belgrade, where he hopes to pick up the
three U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the U.S. is assisting by making arrangements so
that Kyprianou may fly to Belgrade on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Both Rubin and the White House Spokesman Joe Lockhart repeated
U.S. claims that there is no basis for holding the three soldiers
in the first place and they described their arrest as "illegal."
</P>
<P>
It is alleged that the soldiers were part of the troops
dispatched by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) as
potential peacekeeping troops to Kosovo once Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic accepts a peace deal with independence-seeking
Kosovo Albanians.
</P>
<P>
NATO has been bombing Serb targets since March 24 with a
claimed aim of stopping what the NATO said Milosevic's killing and
ethnic cleansing of ethnic Albanians in the Yugoslav province of
Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0180 </DOCNO>
