<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Island Emerges Off Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A new island has newly emerged
off the southwestern coast of Pakistan, the Pakistani Ministry of
Defense said in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The island was first sighted by a local fisherman near River
Hingol's estuary 52 nautical miles (96 kilometers) east of Ormara,
a town in Pakistan's southwestern province of Balochistan, said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
The fisherman reported his discovery to the Pakistan Navy (PN)
in the third week of March, who then carried out a detailed survey
of the area around the island and named it "Jezira Malan."
</P>
<P>
The survey conducted by a PN ship, "Behr Paima," showed that
the island is 220 meters in length, 175 meters in width and 25
meters in height, located 1.6 nautical miles (three kilometers)
from the coast.
</P>
<P>
The soil composition of the island appeared to be mud and brown
sand and some gaseous eruptions were observed on its eastern side
which might be indicative of hydrocarbon deposits in the area,
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The sudden emergence of the island can be attributed to seismic
activities as the area between Ormara and Hingol is known to have
mud volcanoes.
</P>
<P>
The matter has been reported to the Pakistani government and
further investigations are in progress by concerned ministries
with full assistance from the PN, said the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
