<HEADLINE> Philippines President Drops Libel Case Against Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine President Joseph
Estrada announced Thursday his decision to drop a 100-million peso
(about 2.5 million U.S. dollar) libel case he filed against the
Manila Times.
</P>
<P>
The president said in a news release that he accepted the
public apology given by the family that owns the Manila Times, as
printed in the paper's front page Thursday under the column of the
paper's president Robina Gokongwei-Pe.
</P>
<P>
"I think that after the public apology, and I accept the
apology, the book is already closed," the president said.
</P>
<P>
The paper earlier publishing a report alleging that President
Estrada affected a 17-billion dollar deal between the National
Power Corp. and the Argentine firm IMPSA-Asia Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Gokongwei-Pe, owner the Manila Times, wrote in her column
entitled "From the Times President" that "I would like to extend
my sincerest apologies for the anxiety you felt from The Times
story published on February 16, 1999."
</P>
<P>
The article that appeared on the front page of the Manila Times
 became the subject of the libel charges filed against
Gokongwei-Pe along with the members of the company's board of
directors and the editorial board of the paper.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada filed the case on March 9, disgusted over
insinuations in the newspaper report that the Presidential Palace
inserted last-minute amendments to a power contract to favor an
Argentine firm.
</P>
<P>
The public apology, which was reportedly opposed by the
newspaper's editorial board, prompted all the editors of the
Manila Times to file their resignation effective April 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
