<HEADLINE> Mozambique Launches National Campaign on Leprosy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Health Minister Aurelio
Zilhao has called the government departments, communities and
religious leaders and all the citizens to strive for the
elimination of leprosy in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The health minister made the remark at the launching ceremony
of the national campaign to eliminate leprosy Wednesday, the
Noticias daily reported Thursday .
</P>
<P>
Zilhao said that effort of the whole society is needed for the
success of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
The months-long campaign will focus on Nampula, Cabo Delgado,
Zambezia and Nisassa provinces, where half of the estimated 7,000
leprosy patients in the country are located, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The country started a plan to treat the disease in 1982, and
kicked off another plan to offer free treatment to leprosy
patients in 1996, but there are still many leprosy sufferers who
are not treated due to lack of medical institutions in some areas,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's anti-leprosy campaign has got help from the World
Health Organization, which sent its representative Carlos Tiny to
the opening ceremony of the leprosy elimination campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
