<HEADLINE> Thailand Urges APEC to Pay Attention to Social Impact of Economic Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will urge the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) to pay more attention to
the social impacts caused by the current economic crisis, rather
than focusing only on trade and investment issues, a senior
Foreign Ministry official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Thai News Agency quoted Director-General of the Department
of Economic Affairs Kobsak Chutikul as saying that Thailand would
also propose that APEC introduce concrete measures to promote and
enhance human resources development, education and small-scale
businesses.
</P>
<P>
"APEC's members should adopt a multi-dimensional approach so
that the broader-scoped social problems will also be addressed and
will not be overshadowed when the next round of multinational
trade talks under the World Trade Organization (WTO) opens next
year," Kobsak said.
</P>
<P>
APEC trade ministers are scheduled to meet in June to discuss
trade liberalization in six sectors, including rubber, fertilizer,
food, automotive products, oilseeds and oilseed products, and
civil aircraft. 
