<HEADLINE> Nigeria Ready to Meet All Forex Requirements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Nigeria is ready
to meet all the foreign exchange requirements of the authorized
dealers, This Day newspaper Thursday quoted the bank's spokesman
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tony Ede, the spokesman and assistant director for corporate
affairs, said that "we won't have problems meeting the foreign
exchange needs this year."
</P>
<P>
In January, the spokesman said that Autonomous Foreign Exchange
Bank had earmarked about 5.1 billion U.S. dollars to fund the
Autonomous Foreign Exchange Market this year.
</P>
<P>
He said that a budgetary provision of 1.9 billion dollars was
expected from other sources, adding that apart from the two, there
was an additional one billion dollars carried over from the 1998
unspent budget.
</P>
<P>
The central bank spent about 1.462 billion dollars to fund the
exchange market in the first quarter of this year and about 1.4
billion dollars of the total amount were used to finance letters
of credit.
</P>
<P>
During the first quarter of this year, a major development at
the market was the official devaluation of the exchange rate in
March from 86 Naira to 90 Naira to the Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Giving reasons for the devaluation, the bank official said that
it was intended to check the perceived liquidity squeeze and make
the economy stronger. 
</P>
