<HEADLINE> Sugar Price Up by 20% in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The price of sugar has gone up by
20 percent with immediate effect, rural bus fares will go up by 28
percent Friday, the daily Herald reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's Minister of Industry and Commerce Nathan Shamuyarira
said Wednesday that the government had reached an agreement with
sugar producers for a 20-percent price hike.
</P>
<P>
The sugar industry had been pressing the government to award an
increase, saying local sugar was the lowest price in southern
Africa. The industry's export earnings had also dropped as a
result of a sharp fall in world prices, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The government agreed to the increase because it wanted to
safeguard the jobs of thousands of people employed in sugar
estates, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed concern at the price of fertilizer which had
increased six times since February last year. The latest round of
increases was that of between 15 and 20 percent which took effect
last month. 
</P>
