<HEADLINE> Kenya to Host Congo (K) Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has offered to host peace
talks involved all parties of the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) to seek an end to the civil war in the central African
country, the Kenyan Ministry of Foreign Affairs said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
An official from the ministry told Xinhua that Kenyan President
 Daniel arap Moi had volunteered Nairobi as the venue for the
proposed talks, which should include representatives of the
Congolese government of President Laurent Kabila and all rebel
groups.
</P>
<P>
The offer was made in a joint communique issued here Tuesday by
 presidents Moi and Kabila during a two-day visit to Kenya by
President Kabila.
</P>
<P>
However, the communique, available here Thursday, did not
reveal the date for holding the talks.
</P>
<P>
The communique said "President Moi offered Nairobi to be the
venue for the all-inclusive talks and further agreed to consult
with all parties with a view to inviting the DRC government and
all Congolese groups which are stakeholders to attend."
</P>
<P>
President Kabila agreed to meet with the rebels who have waged
an eight month campaign to topple him.
</P>
<P>
Presidents Moi and Kabila had lengthy discussions and agreed on
an urgent need to restore peace in the Congo "to enable Congolese
pursue development activities", the communique said.
</P>
<P>
The communique also noted that "President Kabila expressed his
desire for an urgent end to the conflict in the DRC and said he
was ready for talks with rebels and other shareholders in the
republic." 
</P>
</TEXT>
