<HEADLINE> Tanzania, Malawi to Discuss Regional Corridor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania will send a
30-member delegation to attend a meeting in Malawi to discuss the
construction of the Mtwara Development Corridor, a key regional
trade link.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, to be chaired by Tanzania's Minister of Works,
Anna Abdallah, will make a proposal to lure investors to develop
the corridor, located in southern Tanzania border areas.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Works told Xinhua Thursday
that the minister will leave for Malawi to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Media sources said that the delegation will suggest hosting a
conference in November in Arusha, northern Tanzania, to attract
businessmen to invest in the corridor which will benefit Tanzania,
Malawi, Mozambique and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
After a state visit by the Malawi's President Bakili Muluzi to
Tanzania in January this year, developing the corridor, or
building a highway linking up the deep-water Mtwara Port in
southwestern Tanzania with the Mbamba Bay on Lake Nyasa in the
south, has been put on the agenda of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The corridor will be a shortcut for the transportation of goods
from the Indian Ocean to landlocked Malawi and Zambia. The project
is also expected to spur the economic development of the forgotten
areas in northern Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
However, shortage of funds has hampered the project.
Bureaucracy, poor infrastructure and inadequate facilities are
also cited as a snag to investors in the project.
</P>
<P>
Senior government officials and business community from both
countries are expected to raise their concerns and explore ways to
address the problems during the Malawi meeting.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting on the Mtwara Development Corridor was held
in January this year in Tanzania where more than 100 delegates
from the two countries attended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
