<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Central Bank to Protect Depositors' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Uganda, the central bank
of the east African country, Thursday morning assured the
depositors in the closed Greenland Bank Limited (GBL) of paying
back their money, according to its press release.
</P>
<P>
"Bank of Uganda wishes to reaffirm its commitment to pay fully
all depositors their net credit balances as of the date of
closure. The exercise will start with the insured amount per
depositor," it said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank requests the customers of GBL to be patient
while administrative arrangements are being worked out to effect
payment to eligible depositors.
</P>
<P>
The central bank declared the closure of GBL on April 1, 1999,
citing that the bank was insolvent and has made a loss of one
billion shillings (one million U.S. dollars) in the past two
months alone.
</P>
<P>
The 120,000 depositors of the GBL have been demanding the
government to pay back their money and to sack the director in the
central bank who is responsible for supervising commercial banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
