<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Registers for June Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
registered here Thursday for the June general election.
</P>
<P>
"Insya Allah (With God's permission), we have to succeed with
the general election by holding it fairly and justly," the
president told the press after the registration in the Kuningan
Timur village of South Jakarta, along with his wife, Hasri Ainun
Habibie.
</P>
<P>
He also called on all eligible voters to use their voting
rights at the general election slated for June 7.
</P>
<P>
Habibie said, "All the eligible voters here should take the
benefit of it. This big nation has many times conducted the
general election. They are aware that (voting) is not only a right
(of every citizen) but also a duty."
</P>
<P>
The voter registration process, which has entered its fourth
day, is still relatively quiet as some of the regions have not
completed the establishment of its regional election organization
committee (ppd) and polling committee (pps), such as those in
Central Sulawesi, Central Java and East Timor, officials from the
General Election Commission (KPU) said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jakartans were seen queuing up at voter registration
points across the capital city on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The registration of voters for the forthcoming election
officially began last Monday (April 5) and will continue through
to May 4.
</P>
<P>
The voting right is restricted to citizens aged at least 17
years old, but those who are younger and married are also allowed
to vote.
</P>
<P>
To register, people must produce some form of identification,
such as identification cards, driver's license, marriage
certificate or school diploma.
</P>
<P>
KPU officials estimated that about 128 million of the 202
million population in the country are eligible voters in the June
election, touted as the first democratic poll in over three
decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
