<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Emergency Operation in China Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- the United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) announced today that it had completed its latest
emergency food-aid operation in China by helping 5.7 million
victims of last year's floods.
</P>
<P>
The final batch of rice was distributed last week in 320 of the
worst-affected townships in Anhui, Hubei, Hunan and Jiangxi
provinces, and a total of 285,000 tons of wheat were distributed.
</P>
<P>
The food aid, worth more than 70 million U.S. dollars, was
donated by the United States, Canada, United Kingdom, Switzerland,
Australia, Sweden, Spain and, Denmark, and the government of China
contributed an additional 100,000 tons of rice to the program.
</P>
<P>
The emergency operation was launched at the end of last October
following the severe flooding along the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
During the five month period of the program, the WFP
beneficiaries were able to repair over 79,000 houses and renovate
2,000 kilometers of farm and village roads, and 550,000 hectares
of farmland, 250,000 water wells, and 7,600 kilometers of
irrigation canals were also cleared of silt.
</P>
<P>
The WFP has been working in China since 1979, and has launched
61 food-aid programs worth 859 million U.S. dollar, of which 53
projects have been completed, benefiting more than 30 million
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
