<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Journalists Association Promotes Foreign Exchanges (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Journalists help people get to
know more about the distant world and since China's reforms and
opening-up began two decades ago, more foreign journalists have
kept coming here to get a closer look, providing insights and
intriguing stories to introduce China.
</P>
<P>
They have told overseas readers about the vigor and vitality of
this rapidly-developing country. At the same time though, a large
number of Chinese journalists have gone outside China to give
Chinese readers a look beyond their borders.
</P>
<P>
One of the promoters of exchanges between Chinese and foreign
journalists has been the All-China Journalists Association (ACJA),
which has played a special role as a bridge, according to Liang
Guihe, member of its secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The ACJA had been closed down but resumed its work in 1980 and
has had exchanges with more than 100 countries, involving nearly 1,
000 groups and 5,000 people.
</P>
<P>
This has continued to the present and is perhaps exemplified by
the on-going Press Seminar of China and ASEAN (Association of
Southeast Asian Nations) here, ACJA's first international
convention ever. It has pulled in delegates from 9 countries to
discuss making better use of the mass media for Asian economic
prosperity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Journalists Association Promotes Foreign Exchanges (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ACJA is trying to make China better known around the globe,
Liang explains. For instance, Greece sent a team of journalists,
the first of its kind, here last year. They were so amazed that
they responded by giving China full coverage back home, causing a
wave of interest in China. The Greek speaker of parliament called
for non-interference in other nation's internal affairs after
visiting Tibet.
</P>
<P>
In addition to giving better prospects to friendly media ties,
ACJA provides a source for information for smaller countries and
is significant in helping demonstrate the true nature of China,
Liang says, adding that, "ACJA has always tried to provide a free
and relaxing environment for overseas journalists."
</P>
<P>
More overseas journalists have come to understand the concept
of value of the Chinese, he says, and a large number of well-known
magazines like the US's National Geographic send journalists for
interviews every year. These influential publications are
generally more positive and objective in their coverage, Liang
says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Journalists Association Promotes Foreign Exchanges (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One journalist from Canada's Toronto Star, after seeing China
with his own eyes, said that making use of the negative side of
China by Western journalists is wrong and that he hopes to help
people understand China through his stories.
</P>
<P>
One free-lance journalist with the US's Philadelphia Inquirer
visited rural families on her own and congratulated the village on
its elections.
</P>
<P>
Through various exchanges and through cooperation, Chinese
members of the press have discussed press freedoms and the nature
of the press with their counterparts overseas. China shares a view
with the ASEAN countries that the press should serve society in a
positive way, Liang says.
</P>
<P>
Exchanges between journalists help enhance mutual understanding
and friendship. This year provides a special occasion for
journalists around the globe, on the 50th anniversary of New China
and the return of Macao and ACJA will, as usual, function as a
special venue for professional exchanges and friendly national
ties, Liang says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0222 </DOCNO>
