<HEADLINE> Facts &AMP; Figures: China's Trade Goods Structure in First Two Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Following are the latest facts and
figures about China's foreign trade in the first two months this
year in terms of commodity structures, provided by the General
Administration of Customs.
</P>
<P>
China's exports of primary products in the first two months
this year were valued at 2.515 billion U.S. dollars, down 10.2
percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
Imports of primary products declined 10.7 percent to 2.945
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports of industrial products went down 10.6 percent to 19.877
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports of industrial products went up 8.1 percent to 15.68
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Philippine Bank Credit Remains Tight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Although the Central Bank of the
Philippines lowered its key interest rates and the bellwether
91-day treasury bill rate went down to the pre-crisis level, the
country's bankers are still refraining from smiling at their
borrowers.
</P>
<P>
For the eighth time since the start of this year, the central
bank cut its overnight borrowing and lending rates this week by
another 12.5 basis points to 11.75 percent and 13.75 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The bank has been trying for the past three months to reduce
its rates to prod the country's banks into lending more to get the
economy moving.
</P>
<P>
The rate on the 91-day treasury bill, the benchmark banks use
to price their loans to borrowers, dropped by 29.7 basis points
last Monday to settle at 11.487 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the country's banks continue to gingerly approach the
prospect of more aggressive lending with official figures showing
that for January 1999, at least, bank credit remained weak as net
domestic credit fell 3.8 percent on a year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
Credit risk and credit worthiness of borrowers are the
buzzwords among bankers in the country, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The slack credit growth was due partly to banks' reluctance to
take risks, they said.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of non-performing loans of the country's banking
system climbed to 12.1 percent in January from 10.4 percent in
December and 11.8 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
As a precondition for renewed lending activities, banks will
have to liquidate their non-performing assets first, the analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
Leonillo Coronel, executive director of the Bankers Association
of the Philippines, said the banks are also more concerned right
now over the quality of the loans they extend, instead of the
spreads.
</P>
<P>
"It's a question of credit quality," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many analysts said, there must be "an atmosphere of
credit worthiness" in the economy before banks respond to the
market conditions created by monetary authorities.
</P>
<P>
The banks are still looking for more concrete signs of recovery
before they start lending aggressively, said Sergio Edeza, former
treasury director of the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
With the Asian financial crisis still lingering, the country's
manufacturers, major potential borrowers, are not taking advantage
of the lower rates to tap the necessary capital to expand their
businesses and increase production, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
For example, the automobile and appliance industries were among
the hardest hit by the crisis and lending to these sectors is
still bound to be weak, they said.
</P>
<P>
The reason, they said, is that the expected rebound in consumer
demand may not be large enough.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 to 1997, loan growth in the country outpaced the
growth of gross domestic product (GDP) by 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
But loan portfolio growth of the commercial banks is expected
to post flat to marginal increases this year, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
"It will be anywhere from flat to low growth in 1999," said
April Lee of CitiSecurities.
</P>
<P>
"The most optimistic scenario among the banks we talked to was
a 10-percent loan growth," she said. "But that's optimistic."
</P>
<P>
The analysts believed that the long-awaited trend reversal of
credit will come after 2000, possibly in 2001 along with higher
GDP growth.
</P>
<P>
"Banking is a lag sector," said Worldsec Securities research
head Erico Claudio. "That means the economy has to improve first
before we see any improvement in banks." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
