<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 07:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Residency Revoking Policy Fails: Husseini </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Israel's policy of revoking the
residency status of Palestinians who were born in Jerusalem but
live outside the city has failed, said a senior Palestinian
official.
</P>
<P>
Faisal Husseini, Minister in Charge of Jerusalem Affairs of
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA), was quoted on Thursday
by the local daily Ha'aretz as saying the policy has actually
attracted back to the city a large number of Palestinians for fear
of losing their residency rights.
</P>
<P>
Before 1995, Husseini said, when Israel began to revoke
the residency rights of hundreds of Palestinians each year,
there were about 180,000 Palestinians in the city, and today
the number has climbed to about 215,000.
</P>
<P>
Husseini said that about 6,000 new Palestinian housing units
have been erected in East Jerusalem in the past three year in
response to the Israeli policy.
</P>
<P>
Until 1995, Israel allowed Palestinians to retain their
permanent resident status in Jerusalem as long as they did
not live abroad for more than seven years and returned
periodically to the city.
</P>
<P>
But in 1995, Israel abruptly changed its policy, and many
Palestinians had their identity cards revoked and were forced to
leave the city.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Israeli Interior Ministry has denied
permanent status to Palestinians who have been forced to move
to the city's suburbs because of lack of housing in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, as well as the National Insurance Institute,
denied these Palestinians the rights to live in the holy city on
grounds that their "center of life" had changed to another town,
even if members of their family still live in Jerusalem and their
children study there.
</P>
<P>
The residency status of some 788 Palestinians were revoked in
1998, 606 in 1997, 189 in 1996 and 96 in 1995, according to
Israeli and Palestinian human rights organizations.
</P>
<P>
Five Israeli and 14 Palestinian human rights organizations
last year petitioned the High Court of Justice over the issue
of revoked residency permits for Palestinians. The Court is
scheduled to discuss the issue on April 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
