<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs Of Macao SAR Basic Law (17) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- This is the 17th in a question and
answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special Administrative
Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Can the Central People's Government station troops in the MSAR?
</P>
<P>
Article 14 of the Basic Law of Macao says that the Central
People's Government is responsible for MSAR's defense. The Hong
Kong Basic Law provides for the stationing of troops in Hong Kong
but there is no such provision in the Macao Basic Law. But, the
answer to the question about whether the Central People's
Government will have power to station troops in the Macao Special
Administrative Region is a definite yes.
</P>
<P>
Defense is a general concept and troops are used for defense.
Because the Basic Law already says that the Central People's
Government is responsible for the defense of the MSAR, the
stationing of troops there is something the Central Government
decides in accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
On September 18, 1998, Qian Qichen, Chairman of the MSAR
Preparatory Committee, said at the Committee's Third Plenary
Meeting that, in accordance with Article 14 of the Basic Law, that
the Central People's Government finds it necessary to station an
appropriate number of well trained troops in the MSAR as a symbol
of its exercise of sovereignty over Macao and to ensure social
stability and development there.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government has officially informed the Portuguese
Government of its decision. On September 19, at the closing
session of the Third Pleanry Meeting, Qian emphasized that the
troops stationed there will be responsible for defense only and
will not intervene in the internal affairs of the MSAR.
</P>
<P>
The expense of maintaining them will be covered by the Central
People's Government, whose decision to station them there conforms
with the Basic Law and expresses China's sovereignty over Macao
and is in the interest of the people in Macao.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
