<HEADLINE> Manila Forms Committee to Implement Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to bring lasting peace to
the country, Philippine President Joseph Estrada has created a
high-level committee to help ensure the full implementation of the
peace agreement forged with the Moro National Liberation Front
(MNLF).
</P>
<P>
Under Administrative Order No. 63, the president created the
Cabinet Supervisory Committee to address executive issues and
concerns involving the implementation of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora will head the supervisory
committee, with former Ambassador Manuel Yan, presidential adviser
on the peace process, as vice chairman, the Philippine News Agency
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the administrative order, the committee would provide a
more "focused and more effective direction and supervision" in the
implementation of the peace agreement signed between the
government and the MNLF on September 2, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Other members of the committee include the secretaries of the
Departments of National Defense, Public Works and Highways,
Agriculture, Budget and Management, and Transportation and
Communication.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 peace agreement calls for the establishment of a
Special Zone of Peace and Development (SZOPAD) and the Southern
Philippines Council for Peace and Development in Mindanao.
President Estrada said the accord "signaled the end of decades of
strifes and hostilities" between the government and the MNLF and
"brought hopes to improve the conditions of the Muslim people in
the Southern Philippines"
</P>
<P>
According to the order, the committee will "monitor, in
coordination with concerned agencies, the implementation of
various peace and development projects being undertaken in the
SZOPAD."
</P>
<P>
The committee is also tasked to "address the problems that
hinder the effective implementation of the peace accord," the
order said 
</P>
</TEXT>
