<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs Of Macao SAR Basic Law (18) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- This is the 18th in a question and
answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special Administrative
Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
What are the major administrative affairs the Macao Special
Administrative Region will handle on its own?
</P>
<P>
Administrative affairs are part of the MSAR's autonomy and fall
within the power of its administration. The Basic Law says that
these administrative affairs mainly consist of the following:
</P>
<P>
(1) Economic affairs, including the protection of private
property and foreign investment, budgetary considerations,
financial management, and tax, currency, free trade, industry,
commerce, labor, aviation, shipping, tourism, entertainment, and
environmental protection policies;
</P>
<P>
(2) Cultural and social affairs, including education, public
health, science and technology, culture, the press, publishing,
sports, religion, the professions, social welfare, and the funding
of private organizations;
</P>
<P>
(3) Civil service affairs. Under the Basic Law, the Chief
Executive has the power to appoint and dismiss civil servants and
implement an employment and promotion system for civil servants
and disciplinary action that applies to them;
</P>
<P>
(4) Land management affairs, including the use, development,
and lease of land;
</P>
<P>
(5) Public order, including taking steps to crack down on
illegal activities and protecting the rights and interests of the
people of Macao;
</P>
<P>
(6) Implementing the Basic Law and other laws of the MSAR and
orders from the Central People's Government related to the Basic
Law;
</P>
<P>
(7) External affairs, mainly those authorized by the Central
People's Government; and
</P>
<P>
(8) Administrative orders and decrees. The Chief Executive has
the power to issue administrative orders and adopt and enforce
administrative decrees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 07:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Seek Stronger Ties With Gulf States: King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
said Thursday night that his country would seek further ties with
the Arab states in the Gulf, a traditional stronghold for
Jordanian labor.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Jordan TV following his return from a three-day
visit to Saudi Arabia, the monarch said his talks with Saudi
leaders focused on further developing bilateral ties and
cooperation in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said he hopes to see further strengthening of
relations between Jordan and Saudi Arabia and other Gulf states,
but he denied a report that Jordan is seeking to join the
six-member Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC).
</P>
<P>
"I don't know where that (report) came from. I think we just
need to leave that gossip at this stage," he said.
</P>
<P>
The king was referring to a report by the London-based
newspaper Al Quds Al Arabi which said Monday Abdullah would
officially inform Saudi officials of Jordan's desire to join the
GCC later this year.
</P>
<P>
The paper also quoted senior Arab sources as saying that Saudi
Arabia had initially agreed to Jordan's request.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, founded in 1981 to boost regional cooperation, now
groups Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Bahrain and the United
Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah's visit to Riyadh is part of his efforts to rally
support in the Gulf states for the stagnant economy of his desert
kingdom, and he is also expected to visit Kuwait and the United
Arab Emirates later this month.
</P>
<P>
His visits to the Gulf states are aimed at amending ties which
sifted during the 1990 Gulf Crisis as a result of Jordan's
sympathy with Iraq after the latter invaded Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf states have been the largest market for Jordanian
labor export, which is one of the three pillars of its national
economy along with foreign aid and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials expressed the hope that Abdullah's
just-concluded visit to Riyadh will help reopen the Gulf labor
market for Jordan which was badly affected by the Gulf Crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
