<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT April 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel is to visit
Macedonia and Albania on Sunday in a bid to provide humanitarian
aid to Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry said in a statement Wednesday that
Demirel will visit the two countries to examine the plight of the
Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
Along with Demirel's visit, Foreign Minister Ismail Cem will
meet with his counterparts from the European Union (EU) and other
Balkan countries in Luxembourg on Thursday. (Demirel-Visit-
Macedonia-Albania)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian Defense Ministry will review Russia's
disarmament plan as a result of what is presently occurring in the
Balkans and the new strategies NATO is planning to implement,
Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister, who returned from Tajikstan Wednesday,
told the press that Russia would increase the size of its 1.2
million-strong armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Russia decided to reinforce its combat forces because NATO
intends to implement a new strategy in which the bloc may use
force in any place without approval from the United Nations,
Sergeyev said. (Russia-Disarmarment Plan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The Russian reconnaissance ship sent to the
Mediterranean was monitored by NATO navy, Russian navy command
said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Liman (Estuary), which left the Ukrainian port of
Sebastopol on Friday, is the first of a seven-vessel flotilla from
the Black Sea Fleet that Russia plans to send toward the Yugoslav
coast.
</P>
<P>
The ship is part of Russia's response to NATO bombing on
Yugoslavia. Its declared task is to "collect information" about
the situation around Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the ship entered the Mediterranean, it was monitored
by navy forces from Greece and Turkey, both NATO member states,
the Russian navy command said. (Russian-Ship-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji arrived here from Los
Angeles Wednesday by special plane to continue his eight-day
official visit to the United States at the invitation of President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, who arrived in Los Angeles Tuesday to kick off the visit,
is the first Chinese premier to visit the country in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Washington, the Chinese premier is expected
to have an extensive and in-depth exchange of views with Clinton
on Sino-U.S. ties as well as major international and regional
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Zhu will also co-chair the second meeting of the China-U.S.
Environment and Development Forum with Vice President Al Gore. (
US-China-Zhu-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia hopes that the situation in Yugoslavia does
not produce a negative effect on its relationship with the United
States, said Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov at a press conference
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said that Prime Minister Yevgeny Maksimovich Primakov
called U.S. Vice President Albert Gore on Tuesday in a bid to find
a way to end the Balkan crisis and preserve Russian-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
During the call, Primakov said the Kremlin will make every
effort to reduce the negative effects resulting from the
Yugoslavia situation, although some negative influences were
unavoidable. (Russia-Kosovo-Statement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SOFIA -- The Bulgarian parliament rejected the no-confidence
motion by the opposition against the government's reform of the
national industrial structure by a vote of 139 to 87 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The motion was put to the vote in the presence of Prime
Minister Ivan Kostov who had cut short a visit to Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
On the open ballot, the motion was rejected by the Union of
Democratic Forces (UDF) and the Popular Union, which were joined
by Arlin Antonov of the Alliance for National Salvation (ANS) and
independents Hristo Ivanov and Hristo Petrov. It was backed by the
Socialist-dominated Democratic Left, the Euro-Left and 15 MPs of
the ANS. (Bulgaria-Motion) 
</P>
</TEXT>
