<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tougher Times Predicted In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's economy, which hit low
levels toward the end of last year, appears to be continuing on
another bumpy ride this year, economists have said.
</P>
<P>
The economists described the first quarter of this year as bad
and predicted even tougher times ahead, the Business weekly
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an interview, President of Zimbabwe Economic Society Kennias
 Mafukidze said there were signs that things could get worse.
</P>
<P>
He said the 50 percent inflation level, which the economy was
experiencing was an indication that all was not well.
</P>
<P>
He said: "The major challenge that the country is facing is to
have solid measures to contain inflation and restore
macro-economic stability."
</P>
<P>
President of the Zimbabwe National Chamber of Commerce Nhlanhla
Masuku said the first three months of this year had a mixture of
good and bad aspects. On the good side were impressive results by
companies on the Zimbabwe Stock Exchange, while the high inflation
rate was worrisome.
</P>
<P>
He said while the IMF had not been forthcoming with its
assistance, the aid should not be perceived as the solution to the
country's problems.
</P>
<P>
President of the Confederation of Zimbabwe Industries Kumbirayi
Katsanda said there was need for a sense of urgency on the part of
the government to resolve economic problems.
</P>
<P>
"There is a bleeding in the economy and it is up to the
government to deal with the economic fundamentals but there is an
apparent lack of urgency by the government to do so," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
