<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Constitution Not to be Changed: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambian constitution will not be
altered in 2001 to pave way for one presidential candidate,
Information and Broadcasting Services minister, Newstead Zimba has
said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail newspaper Thursday quoted Zimba, who is also
chief government spokesman, as saying the candidature in the 2001
presidential and general elections will be dependent on the
constitution and that candidates who will not qualify will not
contest.
</P>
<P>
Zambian main opposition party, United National Independence
Party (UNIP) national chairman, Malimab Masheke, told the press
Sunday that his party would fight the Zambian constitution "tooth
and nail" to pave way for its leader, former president Kenneth
Kaunda, to contest the 2001 polls.
</P>
<P>
Zimba said in an interview in Lusaka Wednesday that there had
been a chain of commissions interviewing Zambians country-wide
about who they thought should be eligible to stand as president.
</P>
<P>
He charged that no one was born to rule this country and that
there must be time when leaders defeated in polls or
constitutionally should not continue using other fora to make
unnecessary claims.
</P>
<P>
UNIP information and publicity secretary, Bweendo Mulengela,
had declared that its presidential candidate in the 2001 elections
would be Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda had been ruling the country since its independence in
1964 until 1991, when he was defeated by current President
Frederick Chiluba. He was barred from running for the country's
presidency during the 1996 elections, when a constitutional
amendment was adopted under which foreign nationals and those with
foreign parentage are prohibited from contesting the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda has vowed to contest the post in the next elections
after Ndola High Court declared him stateless at the start of the
month.
</P>
<P>
Zimba emphasized that the government was following the will of
Zambians who had spoken through the past commissions and indicated
that they would not allow themselves to be enslaved.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
