<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Tells Graduates to Seek Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
has suggested local university graduates to seek jobs abroad
because Kenyan labor market could no longer guarantee employment
for all.
</P>
<P>
Moi told local graduates Wednesday to "be open-minded and
strive not only for paid jobs, but more importantly, for
self-employment", the East African Standard reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Our country has continued to experience severe difficulties
which have reduced the capacity of the economy to create adequate
employment opportunities for the large number of people who join
the labor market each year, " Moi said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at at the graduation ceremony of the Jomo Kenyatta
University of Agriculture and Technology, Moi said he was
delighted to encounter more than 300 Kenyan medical doctors
during his recent visit to Botswana, a southern African country.
</P>
<P>
He said that even in Namibia and South Africa, there were
plenty of job opportunities for Kenyan university graduates and
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has suffered low annual economic growth rate since 1997.
The growth rate was 2.3 percent in 1997 and 1.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The president also warned politicians to guard against
misleading Kenyans into believing that money provided by the
World Bank and International Monetary Fund (IMF) was for free.
</P>
</TEXT>
