<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China is Capable of Increasing Grain Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- China still has the potential to
increase its grain supply, and the country plans to raise grain
production through modern science and technology.
</P>
<P>
A Ministry of Agriculture official said that great differences
exist between unit grain output per hectare in various areas,
ranging from 3,000 kilograms to 15,000 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the grain production target can be reached if the
unit output grows by 1 percent annually, and that unit grain
output rose by 3.1 percent on an annual basis from 1950 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
China currently has 35 million hectares of wasteland that can
be used for farming purposes, he said.
</P>
<P>
Science and technology now contributes only 42 percent to
China's grain production, lagging far behind developed countries,
and therefore the country will increase efforts to install agro-
technology nationwide, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
