<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 08:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Cabinet Approves 1999 Budget Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Lebanese cabinet Wednesday
night endorsed the 1999 fiscal budget bill which sets the deficit
at 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bill will be submitted to the parliament for approval.
</P>
<P>
The bill targets revenue for 1999 at 4,990 billion Lebanese
pounds (3.32 billion U.S. dollars), compared with 4,430 billion
pounds (2.95 billion dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The spending was set at 8360 billion Lebanese pounds (about 5.5
billion dollars), compared with 7,186 billion pounds (4.79 billion
dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Information Minister Anwar Khalil told reporters after
the cabinet session on Wednesday night that a new income tax
system would be imposed, replacing the existing flat rate of 10
percent. But, he didn't give any details of the system.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Star Thursday quoted cabinet sources as saying the
government would introduce a 30 percent tax on alcoholic
beverages, tobacco and other non-essential commodities and increase
gasoline price by 2,000 pounds (1.3 dollars) per 20 liters.
</P>
<P>
However, customs duties on raw materials for industry were
lowered on a range of goods.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet also decided to impose a 40 percent price hike on
celluar telephone calls, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese economy is undergoing a record recession since the end
of the 1975-1990 civil war with the public debts having hit 18
billion U.S. dollars, one of the highest in the world on per
capita basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians Lose US$7 Billion on Gambling Yearly: ABS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Australians lost a record 11
billion Australian dollars (6.93 billion U.S. dollars) on gambling
in the financial year of 1997-1998, delivering a fat increase in
profits for the industry's owners.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented 595 Australian dollars (374 U.S.
dollars) for every man, woman and child in the country over the
year with a population of 18 million, according to the figures
released here Thursday by the Australian Bureau of Statistics
(ABS).
</P>
<P>
The 11 billion Australian dollars amounted to 2 percent of the
country's gross domestic product, or more than what was spent on
the other great vices, alcohol and tobacco, combined. Or in even
starker terms, for every dollar Australian households spent on
food in the past financial year, they lost 27 cents gambling.
</P>
<P>
The losses in the past financial year were a massive 40 percent
higher than the 7.8 billion Australian dollars (4.9 billion U.S.
dollars) lost in the financial year of 1994-1995.
</P>
<P>
Some of the biggest winners from the increase in gambling have
been pub owners. They more than doubled their profit margins from
gaming activities over the three years, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
It said pubs, taverns and bars with gambling facilities enjoyed
an operating profit margin of 8.6 percent in the past financial
year ending on June 30, 1998, more than double the 3.9-percent
margin they took in the 1994-1995 year.
</P>
<P>
The huge increase in margins helped spread poker machines into
more pubs. The ABS noted a 20-percent rise in the number of pubs
with gambling facilities to 2,785 at the end of June 1998.
</P>
<P>
Poker machines remained Australia's most popular form of
gambling and actually boosted their share of the industry's
takings to 4 billion U.S. dollars, or 57.6 percent, up from 2.4
billion U.S. dollars, or 50.5 percent in the 1994-1995 year.
</P>
<P>
New South Wales state, of which Sydney is the capital, remained
the biggest gambling state although neighboring state Victoria, of
which Melbourne is the capital, rapidly gained ground over the
three-year period and was growing the fastest in terms of takings.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Creates Gardens for World Horticulture Exposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province has
prepared two gardens, the Qilu Garden and the Peony Garden, for
the upcoming '99 Kunming World Horticulture Exposition.
</P>
<P>
A provincial government spokesman said Shandong will be the
only Chinese province with two outdoor exhibition areas.
</P>
<P>
The exposition will be held in Kunming, capital of southwest
China's Yunnan Province, between May 1-October 31 and is expected
to attract participants from 93 countries and international
organizations. Some 10 million people from China and abroad are
expected to attend the event.
</P>
<P>
The Qilu Garden, which covers an area of 1,720 square meters,
feature Mount Taishan, the Baotu Springs, and Confucian culture.
In addition to some 2,100 ornamental plants from the province, the
garden has dozens of carved stones and tablets with inscriptions
depicting the province's major scenic spots and historic sites, as
well as historical figures.
</P>
<P>
The 900-square-meter Peony Garden exhibits around 500 different
kinds of peonies from the city of Heze in Shandong.
</P>
<P>
Heze, dubbed the "home of peonies," grows hundreds of kinds of
peonies on more than 600 hectares of land each year, and is the
world's largest peony producing and export center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
