<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Sri Lanka Faces Uncertain Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is facing an uncertain
political future as the ruling People's Alliance (PA) narrowly won
the polls at the five crucial provincial council elections,
analysts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The PA of President Chandrika Kumaratunga gained all the five
councils at stake in the polls on Tuesday, four of which were held
formerly by the main opposition United National Party (UNP).
</P>
<P>
Despite opposition party allegations of election violence and
violations, the PA victory in holding Western Province and
additionally winning Central, North Central, Uva and Sabaragamuwa
provinces is considered significant.
</P>
<P>
The historic victory is considered a personal triumph for
President Kumaratunga and an overwhelming endorsement of her
leadership.
</P>
<P>
The victory also showed that the UNP has not been accepted by
the country as an alternative government.
</P>
<P>
However, the PA's margin of victory against the UNP was
extremely thin.
</P>
<P>
Overall in the five provinces the PA obtained 46.25 percent or
2,105,546 votes against the UNP's 43.48 percent or 1,979,546
votes, giving the PA a majority of 2.27 percent or 126,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
The ruling coalition won 120 out of the 263 seats while the UNP
got 112. The remaining went to smaller parties.
</P>
<P>
The PA got enough seats to form the administration on its own
only in North Central Province. It will have to depend on Tamil
and Muslim parties' support for forming the administration in the
four provinces of Western, Uva, Central and Sabaragamuwa.
</P>
<P>
In the 1994 presidential elections, the PA won a convincing 62
percent of the votes. But the highest percentage received by the
ruling party in Tuesday's voting was 53 percent in one province.
</P>
<P>
In the most populous Colombo district, the ruling party
garnered a mere 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the ruling party is losing momentum as President
Kumaratunga's early promises to end Sri Lanka's civil war remain
unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
Given the decline in popularity, the ruling party may feel
hesitant about advancing the parliamentary and presidential
elections due next year.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here said the tight results showed that neither party
has immediate answers to the difficult problems Sri Lanka faces
such as a slowing economy and the 16-year war against the
separatist Tamil Tiger rebels.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's gross domestic product expanded by a strong 6.4
percent in 1997. It is estimated to have grown by only 4 to 4.5
percent in 1998 and officials have forecast lower economic growth
rates for 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam rebels have been fighting
the Sri Lankan government for a separate Tamil homeland in the
country's north and east since 1983.
</P>
<P>
The UNP improved on their 1997 performance in local government
elections and appeared to have won the minority Tamil and Muslim
votes in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
In the capital of Colombo, the UNP won overwhelmingly in areas
where the minority Tamils are predominant, indicating the
minorities had swung from the ruling PA.
</P>
<P>
However, the UNP, which ruled the country for 17 continuous
years from 1977, has been accused of bribery, corruption and being
responsible for the disappearance of thousands of persons during
its rule. And it has found it difficult to fend off these
accusations.
</P>
<P>
In addition, its current leadership is faced with serious
differences within the party itself which has damaged its image
among the public.
</P>
<P>
The Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna (JVP), or People's Liberation
Front, gained 5.46 percent of votes or 15 seats, emerging as the
third largest party in the country.
</P>
<P>
The JVP, which was responsible for the youth uprising of the
early 1970s and the subsequent period of terror in the late 1980s,
has made a significant breakthrough into the mainstream of
politics in the five provinces.
</P>
<P>
While it was expected to have performed better, observers
believe that it has still not been able to impress on the country
that it is no longer seeking an armed rebellion but a place in the
administration through democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
Despite the emerging JVP, the main battle is still being fought
between the PA and UNP in the parliamentary and presidential
elections due next year. But it is too early to say which party
will gain the upper hand as the civil war is dragging on and the
economy is slowing down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
