<HEADLINE> Shanghai Farmers Earning More Than Others In Rural China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Farmers on the outskirts of
Shanghai continued to lead farmers in other parts of the country
last year in earnings.
</P>
<P>
Per capita annual incomes of Shanghai farmers were 5,400 yuan
in 1998, up 2.5 percent from 1997, according to the Shanghai Rural
Social and Economic Survey Team.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of the rapid development of township
enterprises and a rural service industry that provide work for
about 70 percent of the local farmers. Non-farming incomes account
for 71.6 percent of their total earnings, a 0.8 percentage point
increase from 1998. Farming-related incomes fell 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the growth in annual incomes slowed to a record low in
recent years, according to Cheng Ying, a member of the survey team,
which studied 600 households, where 44 percent were earning less
than the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
