<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ESCAP Expects Mild Economic Recovery in the Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SINGAPORE, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Economic and Social
Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) of the United Nations
has expected the 1999 will see a mild economic recovery in the
ESCAP region.
</P>
<P>
In its Economic and Social Survey of Asia and the Pacific 1999
released here Thursday, ESCAP said that barring any further shocks
in the financial markets, some positive development will generate
a mild recovery in the region towards the latter part of 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the survey, ESCAP gave a forecast of 3.6 percent GDP growth
of the developing economies of the ESCAP region in 1999, with a
5.6 percent-growth forecast for South and South-West Asia, 0.4
percent for South-East Asia and 4.4 percent for East and
North-East Asia.
</P>
<P>
Elaborating the survey at a press conference this morning on
behalf of the ESCAP, Tan Song Chuan, Managing Director of the
Singapore Trade Development Board Consulting (STDBC) said the
worst is over for the region with Thailand and South Korea leading
recovery and Malaysia a step behind.
</P>
<P>
However, ESCAP noted that there are concerns regarding the
sustainability of the improvement in the light of only limited
progress in financial sector restructuring, the continued credit
crunch, the still growing burden of non-performing loans and no
major recovery of exports.
</P>
<P>
In reviewing the growth performance in the ESCAP region, ESCAP
said GDP growth rate of developing economies of the ESCAP region
dropped to 0.2 percent in 1998 from 5.8 percent in 1997 with
South-East Asia experiencing one of the worst years on record .
</P>
<P>
Out of 19 developing countries of mainland Asia, seven suffered
negative growth in 1998 compared to none in 1996 and only one in
1997, it said, adding a number of countries are experiencing
severe social problems in the form of mounting unemployment,
increased incidence of poverty, sharp dropouts of school students
and large cut in consumption of health services.
</P>
<P>
On recent positive developments. ESCAP highlighted a downturn
trend in interest rates, recovery and stabilization in exchange
rates and stock markets, increase in foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
On global economic environment, ESCAP said growth rate in world
economy fell to 1.7 percent in 1998 compared to 3.2 percent in
1997. and trade growth in volume terms declined even more
precipitately, from 9.7 percent in 1997 to 3.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
ESCAP underlined that a number of development in world economy
have adverse implication for the ESCAP region, referring to weak
state of Japan economy, the possible slowdown in EU and the likely
flattening of growth in the U.S. economy in 1999.
</P>
<P>
ESCAP also drew attention to a major uncertainty in the behavior
of capital flows, saying "world financial market have displayed
increased volatility, commodity prices have weakened and
international capital flows to developing countries, especially
debt flows, have declined."
</P>
<P>
New developments suggest that non-FDI (foreign direct
investment) private capital is not likely to start flowing into
the region soon on any substantial scale and FDI flows may remain
concentrated in acquisitions of existing assets rather than
creating new production capacity, ESCAP noted.
</P>
<P>
On measures to be taken to ensure a recovery, ESCAP said
policies at the national, regional and international levels are
needed to overcome the problems created by the economic crisis as
government's ability to address social problems has been
constrained by reduced revenues and, in some cases, by the
conditionalities of the bailout packages.
</P>
<P>
Consideration needs to be given to reforming the international
architecture and intensifying regional cooperation, including
consideration of the establishment, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Pork Prices Plummet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua)-- Pork prices have been in a downward
spiral since the beginning of the year, causing severe losses to
pig farms, according to a Ministry of Agriculture survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted in 400 counties, found that, in March,
piglet prices fell by an annual rate of 50 percent and pork fell
21.8 percent to 6.42 yuan per kilo and 9.9 yuan per kilo
respectively.
</P>
<P>
This cost farmers about 100 yuan more per pig. Sales of breeder
pigs were down by more than half even at prices that were down
more than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the sharp price decline to an excess of pork.
</P>
<P>
Pigs were at their most profitable level in 1997, but the
aggressive expansion of pig raising and increased pork output have
been met with shrinking market demand.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that increased beef, mutton, and poultry output
has eaten into the pork market. The three items grew from 20.2
percent of the meat market in 1990 to 32.7 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Consumer incomes have had slower growth as well, and the high-
income consumers are tending to buy more vegetables, eggs, and
milk while low-income people are spending less on meat.
</P>
<P>
To reverse this trend, the ministry recently called a meeting
of officials from Shandong, Sichuan, and other pork-producing
provinces for a strategy discussion. As a solution, it says it has
decided to break up the monopoly on pork production and sales and
try to create a more natural market that allows for a smoother
flow of information and sales that respond purely to market demand.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ministry plans to come down hard on charges
and illicit fees levied on farmers and will make a greater effort
to promote pork processing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Tiger In Shanghai Has Three Cubs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A 4-year-old South China tiger
has given birth to three cubs at the Shanghai Zoo.
</P>
<P>
The mother's milk was insufficient to care for the cubs and in
less than three days she left them to the care of zookeeper Gu
Wenyang who has been working at the Shanghai Zoo for more than 30
years.
</P>
<P>
The cubs now get four meals a day with 55 milliliters of
powdered milk and to protect them from the changeable weather, the
room temperature is set at 27 degrees centigrade.
</P>
<P>
The eldest cub, a male, weighed 1,500 grams at birth, the
second, 1,350 grams, and the third, 1,250. Half a month of growth
has added 50 grams each to their weight.
</P>
<P>
But zoo workers are worried about inbreeding among South China
tigers, resulting from the decrease in numbers of the rare species.
There are 53 South China tigers at 21 zoos in China.
</P>
<P>
The South China tiger has a life span of 18 to 20 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
