<HEADLINE> Plastic Sheeting Help Fight Drought In Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Hu Shanmin, a farmer in Fuping
County in China's Shaanxi Province, says that the green wheat
sprouts in his field are a miracle at a time when people are
worrying about withered crops during the long period of drought.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi had suffered from drought since last October.
</P>
<P>
The 62-year-old Hu says that his seedlings would have withered
if he hadn't used plastic sheeting. He expects to have a good
harvest this year as one of the farmers who have benefited from
the new technology, which has been applied to 147,000 ha of
farmland in the province since 1997.
</P>
<P>
Per-ha. grain output of the province was increased by about 1,
500 kg. and 1,200 cubic meters of water was saved when the plastic
sheeting started being used to protect crops and retain moisture.
</P>
<P>
The technology has been welcomed by farmers on China's loess
plateau. In 1998, the provincial government offered 75 million
yuan in loans to help apply the technology to 130,000 ha. of
farmland. That is expected to reach 270,000 ha. next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Chinese Sentenced To Prison Terms For Logging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Eight people accused of illegal
logging who attacked forest rangers when they were challenged in
Minxian County in northwest China's Gansu Province have been
sentenced to various prison terms.
</P>
<P>
The longest was for 6 years. Another person caught who was
below the age of 16 was released.
</P>
<P>
On January 23, the 12 forest rangers involved in the clash were
seriously injured when several hundred villagers turned on them as
they tried to persuade the villagers not to cut trees. Five police
cars were also damaged during the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The county's procurator department investigated the case and
charged 9 of them with interfering with law enforcement and
inciting violence.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government introduced last October a ban on the
cutting of trees and closed down 30 lumber companies and outlets
to improve the condition of forest areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
