<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Sets up More Special Courts to Protect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government will set
up 10 more special courts to curb the violence against women and
children in the country.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the decision of an inter-ministerial meeting
in November last year, the Ministry of Women and Family Welfare
has selected 10 districts to set up the courts to accelerate trial
for repression on women and children, on the basis of the
intensity of crime and violent incidents, The Bangladesh Observer
daily newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government previously asked commissioners of 42 districts
to submit reports on repression on women and children from July
1997 to June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The highest number of cases against women and children was 649,
recorded in Sirajganj district, about 113 Kilometers northwest of
here, and the lowest number of 118 was recorded in Manikganj
district, 50 kilometers northwest of the capital.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 10 special courts in 10 of the country's
64 districts to deal with the repressive incidents against women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
