<HEADLINE> Yugoslav, Greek Soccer Teams Play Goodwill Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 7 (Xinhua) -- In a show of defiance of air
raids by NATO against Yugoslavia, soccer teams from Yugoslavia
and Greece played a goodwill match here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The "guerrilla team" from the Yugoslav federation and the AEK
team from Greece entered a stadium in Belgrade bedecked with a
large banner with a slogan reading "stop war, stop air strikes."
</P>
<P>
Players and an audience of 15,000 stood in silent tribute
before the match started to mourn those who died in the NATO
bombing which entered the 15th day Wednesday. The match ended 1-1.
The benefits from the match will be donated to relatives of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
Among the audience were Prime Minister of the Serb Republic
Mirko Marjanovic and celebrities from all walks of life.
</P>
<P>
President of the Serb Republic Milan Milutinovic expressed
gratitude to Greek players for their goodwill trip to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav people will safeguard the nation's independence
and freedom and will overcome difficulties and seek a political
solution to the Kosovo issue, the president said while meeting the
Greek team Wednesday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
