<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Asks Manila to Pay at Once Ramos Obligations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has asked the Philippine government to immediately pay 68
billion pesos (1 U.S. dollar is equal to about 40 pesos) in
obligations left behind by the previous Ramos administration,
warning that delays in settling the unpaid accounts will hurt the
country's credit rating abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Times reported Thursday that the IMF also urged the
Estrada administration to avoid piling up similar obligations,
which are mostly owed to contractors undertaking government
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
Members of a visiting IMF team raised the issue Wednesday,
right at the start of their two-week review of the country's
economic performance for the first quarter of the year, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The infrastructure-oriented Ramos administration left behind
108 billion pesos in unpaid accounts owed to contractors. The
Estrada administration, which took over last June 30, has so far
settled only 40 billion.
</P>
<P>
While the IMF officials acknowledged that the financial crisis
was partly to blame for the accumulation of the accounts payable
under the Ramos administration, they nevertheless pointed out that
it must also be due to some "systemic problems" caused by weak
revenues and the propensity to borrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
