<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supachai Prepares to fight Until last Minute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Prime Minister
Supachai Panitchpakdi will go to Geneva next week to compete for
the top job at the World Trade Organization "until the last
minute", according to Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan.
</P>
<P>
If Supachai lost, it would be for reasons other than his
academic Qualifications, his quality as a candidate and the Thai
government's commitment to free trade, Surin was quoted Thursday
by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Supachai is competing with New Zealand's former prime Minister
Mike Moore, to replace Renato Ruggiero as the WTO's new
director-general.
</P>
<P>
The WTO General Council is due to meet on April 14 for what is
expected to be the final decision on the matter. Ruggiero steps
down on April 30, and the WTO's 134 members have been trying to
form a consensus on his successor since October last year.
</P>
<P>
Supachai is currently in Europe and due to stop in Germany
Thursday before continuing to Portugal, Greece and Belgium.
</P>
</TEXT>
