<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Fails to Reach Paddy Production Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The paddy production of Myanmar
reached over 17 million tons annually in the last few years
beginning 1996-97 fiscal year against the annual target set at 20
million tons.
</P>
<P>
"The targets could not be realized as expected. Obstacles are
being faced in developing the agricultural sector as it is at
large and related with many other sectors," Myanmar leader Senior
General Than Shwe was quoted by Thursday's official newspaper The
New Light of Myanmar as saying.
</P>
<P>
"However, various means are being sought in developing the
sector as projected," Than Shwe, chairman of the Myanmar State
peace and Development Council, told officials of three divisions
Tuesday on his inspection tour.
</P>
<P>
He added that invitations have been extended to national
entrepreneurs who have capital and expertise to effectively and
fully use the nation's land resources as the new force.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year when the government started
allowing private entrepreneurs to reclaim vacant, virgin, fallow
and wetlands in the country, a total of 467,370 hectares of such
lands in six divisions and states have been reclaimed to cultivate
crops to boost the country's agriculture products.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's paddy production
has been dropping steadily in the past few years, falling from 19
million tons in 1995-96 to 17.66 million tons in 1996-97 and again
to 17.3 million tons in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's agriculture, accounting for 36 percent of the gross
domestic products (GDP) and 35 percent of the export in value,
grew by 2.9 percent in output value in 1997-98 against the target
of 6.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The national GDP rose by 4.6 percent in the year against the
target of 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figures for 1998-99 which ended March have not yet been
published.  
</P>
</TEXT>
