<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Parliament Rejects No-confidence Motion Against Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- The Bulgarian parliament rejected
the no-confidence motion by the opposition against the
government's reform of the national industrial structure by a vote
of 139 to 87 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The motion was put to the vote in the presence of Prime
Minister Ivan Kostov who had cut short a visit to Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
On the open ballot, the motion was rejected by the Union of
Democratic Forces (UDF) and the Popular Union, which were joined
by Arlin Antonov of the Alliance for National Salvation (ANS) and
independents Hristo Ivanov and Hristo Petrov. It was backed by the
Socialist-dominated Democratic Left, the Euro-Left and 15 MPs of
the ANS.
</P>
<P>
"We are aware of the weaknesses, mistakes and delay of reform
in some sectors, but it is not a reason to stop at this point,"
the prime minister told the MPs after the vote. He thanked the
parliamentary majority and independents for the trust they had put
on the government, adding that the vote had made the cabinet feel
stronger and more confident in what it is doing.
</P>
<P>
"This day was a success for Georgi Purvanov, the leader of the
opposition Socialist party, because he managed to close the circle
and to lead the Socialist party throughout the vote without having
to admit the failure of the economic policy of the party," said
Kostov.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the leaders of the Euro-Left and the ANS,
Alexander Tomov and Ahmed Dogan, have been used to covering up the
failures of the Socialist party.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the parliament, Georgi Purvanov said the country
needs a new policy and a new team to implement it. In his view,
the vote foretold the "death" of the reformist majority,
consolidation of the opposition, and retailoring of parliamentary
space.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to share the responsibility for the policy of
liquidation, which we do not support," Dimiter Loudjev said on
behalf of the ANS. He warned that social peace in the country is
in jeopardy and stressed the role of the Movement for Rights and
Freedoms in preserving ethnic peace in Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
This vote ushered in a new political model. The opposition put
the beginning of a powerful national movement of versatile
composition, said Euro-Left's Alexander Tomov. He said the
government is pursuing a wrong macroeconomic policy and the key
mechanisms of the currency board are at risk.
</P>
<P>
UDF floor leader Ekaterina Mihailova said the opposition used
the motion ahead of local elections to conceal the difficult days
that are in store for Bulgaria. She asked whether those, who want
a new policy and a new government team, have the courage and a
program to face the voters.
</P>
<P>
The ruling majority is aware of what is in store for it. It is
the most unpopular step of the structural reform, but they will
not escape their responsibility, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
