<HEADLINE> Vietnam's War Veterans Protest Against NATO's Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnam War Veterans'
Association (VWVA) have voiced strong protests against NATO's
military escalation against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and
demanded end to bombing of Yugoslavia, Vietnam's English daily
Vietnam News reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 1.5 million-member association said in a statement issued
recently that all war veterans in Vietnam fully support the just
struggle and determination by the Yugoslav people against
aggressive acts for national independence, sovereignty and
territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
The association said NATO's brutal air attacks against
Yugoslavia's territory including Belgrade had caused heavy losses
and serious consequences for the population, particularly women
and children, created a movement of refugees, complicated the
Kosovo problem, and jeopardized peace and stability in the Balkans
regions, Europe, as well as the world.
</P>
<P>
By launching military attacks, the VWVA said, NATO and the
United States have seriously violated the U.N. Charter and
international law, and created a dangerous precedent in
international relations.
</P>
<P>
The VWVA also fully supported the Vietnam's Foreign Ministry's
March 25 statement, and the search for a long-term peaceful
solution for the Kosovo problem so as to bring peace to
Yugoslavian people to rebuild their country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
