<HEADLINE> Exports Between ALADI Countries Fell 5.5 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition, exports from ALADI member countries fell 1.5
percent, from 211.91 billion dollars in 1997, to 208.64 billion
dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Global external sales of member states were reduced from 257.42
billion dollars in 1997, to 251.65 billion dollars in 1998, which
represents a reduction of 2.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Inter-regional imports registered a slight fall of 0.8 percent,
from 46.47 billion dollars in 1997 to 46.12 billion in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Global imports of ALADI members were 289.02 billion dollars in
1998.
</P>
<P>
The General Secretary said the causes of the variations in
inter-regional commerce were attributed to a strong fall in
international prices of diverse manufactured products and raw
materials, and from consequences of the financial crisis of Asia
and Russia, and included natural disasters which affected some of
the ALADI countries.
</P>
<P>
Rojas said the economic growth of Latin American countries had
been reduced from more than 5 percent in 1998 to less than half of
that rate in 1998, under the influence of the Asian and Russian
crisis.
</P>
<P>
ALADI is formed by Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile, Columbia,
Ecuador, Peru, Paraguay, Mexico, Venezuela and Uruguay. 
</P>
