<HEADLINE> Foreigners allowed Greater Business Engagement in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The House has passed a bill to
allow foreigners to open a variety of new businesses and even hold
a majority shareholding in a company, Thursday's Bangkok Post
reported.
</P>
<P>
Members unanimously approved the third reading of the Alien
Business Bill on Wednesday, in a bid to attract more foreign
investment and boost and sagging economy.
</P>
<P>
The bill, to be forwarded to the senate on Friday, allows
foreigners to engage in the following fields:
</P>
<P>
-- Construction of infrastructure which relies on "special"
technology and expertise if a foreigner can provide a minimum of
500 million baht (13.5 million U.S. dollars) in operating funds;
</P>
<P>
-- Brokerage in the stock market or farm futures market;
</P>
<P>
-- Accounting, legal and engineering services;
</P>
<P>
-- Milling rice and making flour from rice or other crops, and
</P>
<P>
-- Import or export businesses, with a minimum operating fund
of 100 million baht (2.7 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
But the bill bans foreigners from a number of businesses for
"special reasons". These businesses include:
</P>
<P>
-- Publishing newspapers and broadcasting radio or television
programs;
</P>
<P>
-- Farming;
</P>
<P>
-- Raising livestock;
</P>
<P>
-- Logging and making products from timber;
</P>
<P>
-- Fishing in Thai territorial waters;
</P>
<P>
-- Making products from Thai herbs;
</P>
<P>
-- Selling Thai artifacts and historical objects;
</P>
<P>
-- Making Buddha images and monk's bowls, and
</P>
<P>
-- Dealing in parcels of land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
