<HEADLINE> Muscovites Rally Against NATO's Strikes on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Some 20,000 Muscovites staged a
demonstration Wednesday to protest NATO's blatant bombardment of
Yugoslavia and voice support for the country's tenacious
resistance to aggressors.
</P>
<P>
The rally, held near the Kremlin Palace, lasted for about two
hours. It was the first large-scale organized protest in Moscow
since the start of the U.S.-led NATO military strikes against
Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
Many demonstrators held placards with anti-NATO slogans on them
and carried target-shaped pictures on their breasts, which have
turned into a symbol of Yugoslav resistance to aggressors.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the rally, the leaders of the Fatherland Movement,
the Russian Communist Party and other parties made speeches at the
rally. They demanded NATO halt strikes against Yugoslavia, restart
negotiations on the Kosovo issue, and appealed to Russian leaders
to provide stronger support for the Yugoslav people.
</P>
<P>
An appeal adopted by the rally said the NATO's aggression
caused the exodus of refugees out of Kosovo and made the Yugoslav
people suffer.
</P>
<P>
It said those who seek hegemony in the world have banished the
historic lessons from their minds and try to ignore the world
order established after World War II.
</P>
<P>
The appeal also said that Russia will never ignore its "
Yugoslav brothers'" fate. 
</P>
