<HEADLINE> International Volunteers Enthusiastic About Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIANDU (Zhejiang), April 8 (Xinhua) -- "I like you", a Japanese
girl says to a Chinese boy who replies "I like you more", not as a
declaration of love, but as part of an international exchange.
</P>
<P>
They are part of a group of volunteers who are here for the '99
China International Young Volunteers Camp for environmental
protection and cultural exchanges. They come from Asia, Europe,
Oceania and North America and have shown great interest in
learning Chinese even though they use English at camp.
</P>
<P>
"I like you" was the first thing they learned to say in Chinese
and next came "hello". A 66-year-old man from Japan has brought
books on how to learn Chinese and always takes notes when he comes
across new words. Other volunteers say he is a good example of
combining principle with practice.
</P>
<P>
An Australian who is studying environmental protection at
Beijing University has become an expert among volunteers, but he
is modest and looks shy when the other volunteers say his Chinese
is as good as that of Da Shan, a Canadian who is proficient in
Chinese. When he sang a Chinese song "If There Were No Communist
Party, There'd Be No New China", everybody was stunned by his
fluency. 
</P>
