<HEADLINE> IMF Advises Manila to Boost Revenue Collections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) is advising the Philippine government to step up prescribed
reforms for the fiscal sector to boost revenue collections, the
Philippine Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, a visiting IMF mission which held
an initial meeting with the Philippine Finance Department
Wednesday said the Fund wants a "mapping-out of an action plan for
1999" to end the persistent income shortfalls by the country's
Bureau of Internal Revenue (BIR).
</P>
<P>
BIR, the top revenue earner of the country, pulled in only
337.175 billion pesos (1 U.S. dollar is equal to about 40 pesos)
last year, vis-a-vis the 347.675 billion pesos set by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
This brings the 1998 collection (Including those of the Bureau
of Treasury, the Bureau of Customs, and other agencies) to 462.52
billion pesos, down from 1997's 471.843 billion pesos.
</P>
<P>
Government officials pointed out that the 7.1% growth in BIR's
earnings last year from the 314.497 billion pesos recorded in
1997, was lower than the 9.7% inflation rate in 1998, connoting a
declining tax effort.
</P>
<P>
Such a problem poses a threat to government's aim of attaining
a robust economic growth this year.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the IMF was also concerned over the
government's unprogrammed overspending seen in the last months of
1998 that resulted in a bigger-than-expected fiscal deficit of 50
billion pesos. This exceeded the 49 billion pesos ceiling placed
by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The government has forged a "precautionary arrangement" with
the IMF in the summer of last year, obliging the former to carry
out economic reforms in exchange for a 1.4 billion U.S. dollars
financing to be disbursed in tranches until March 2000.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has allowed the government to incur a deficit of as
much as 68.4 billion this year, to facilitate the Philippine
government's "pump-priming" agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
