<HEADLINE> 3,833 Hectares of Poppy Fields Destroyed in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 8 (Xinhua) -- A total of 3,833 hectares of poppy
plantations illegally grown in remote areas of the country's
northern and eastern parts were destroyed in 1998-99 poppy
cultivation season from November 1998 to March 14, 1999, official
newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The poppy fields, jointly destroyed by army units, local
intelligence units, police force and local people, were in Shan,
Kayah and Kachin states and Sagaing division.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are going on to search and destroy the illegal poppy
plantations, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official statistics, a total of 32,787
hectares of poppy fields in the past ten years from 1988 to 1998
were destroyed, deterring the yield of 356.17 tons of opium during
the period.
</P>
<P>
According to Myanmar official statistics, in 1998 there were
61,236 hectares of poppy cultivation in the entire country that
would yield 665.28 tons of raw opium and could be refined into
66.52 tons of heroin, while the State Department of the United
States said in its statement issued in March 1998 that there were
157,089 hectares of poppy cultivation that would produce 2,365
tons of raw opium and 197 tons of heroin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
