<HEADLINE> Peruvian President Criticizes NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori
criticized NATO's bombing of civilians in Yugoslavia on Wednesday
and said the conflict in Kosova should be resolved in a peaceful
manner by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"This cannot be justified" he emphasized, after stating that he
had been observing the air attacks on Belgrade on the television.
</P>
<P>
"Grave precedents are being established by the NATO bombing,
which puts civilian populations at risk in one way or another. We
believe this to be intolerable" he added.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori also said the bombing of civilians "is progressively
worsening, and constitutes a magnificent opportunity for returning
the issue to the UN, by way of its Security Council, to the role
which the international community assigned to it after the end of
World War II."
</P>
<P>
"The UN and its Security Council cannot be ignored or replaced
by a regional organization" said Fujimori at a press conference
from the Government Palace.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the help of his country "at the request of the UN
in any conflict, such as that of Kosova, when it is requested
through civilized channels and not through debatable actions which
are receiving world-wide criticism."
</P>
<P>
"Peace continues to be the most costly human right, for this
reason we emphasize that we cannot put peace at risk, we must
strengthen it," he concluded.  
