<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portugal Threatens to Halt Tripartite Talks on E Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Portugal Wednesday threatened to
abandon United Nations-sponsored talks with Indonesia, should
violence against civilians continue in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Ana Gomes, the Portuguese special envoy for Indonesia, said her
country will withdraw from the talks if military personnel fail to
end the rising tide of violence.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with jailed pro-independence East
Timorese leader Xanana Gusmao at his detention house in Central
Jakarta, Gomes said continued violence could threaten the
reconciliation process in the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
She quoted Xanana as saying the latest bloody clashes between
pro and anti-independence factions claimed 49 lives in Liquica
regency, East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Another 70 casualties were reported over the past two months in
East Timor, Gomes said, adding that right now, tensions are
spreading to the regencies of Baucau and Viqueque.
</P>
<P>
"We think that an international investigation is indeed
necessary to establish what has happened in Liquica," Gomes was
quoted by Indonesian newspapers Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
She said the violence in Liquica was aimed at disrupting
tripartite talks between Indonesia, Portugal and the United
Nations which are scheduled to resume later this month.
</P>
<P>
Portugal demanded that Indonesian security authorities deal
with the situation more seriously, otherwise it will withdraw from
the tripartite peace negotiations on East Timor, she added.
</P>
<P>
Gomes also clarified Xanana's earlier controversial instruction
to his followers to undertake a general popular insurrection
against armed militia groups. She said he only "authorized his
people to exercise self-defense against the aggression".
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, the Indonesian Armed Forces (ABRI)
rejected claims by pro-independence East Timorese that 49 people
had been killed in Liquica regency.
</P>
<P>
"It is not true," ABRI spokesman Major General Syamsul Ma'arif
said, adding that the military would investigate the claim.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Minister of Justice Muladi Wednesday said that the
government would review its policy of housing Xanana in his
present special detention quarters "if it was true that Xanana
declared a war against ABRI and Indonesians".
</P>
<P>
The aim of placing Xanana in special detention "was so he could
contribute more effectively to the settlement of the East Timor
problem... not for declaring a war like that, whatever the
reason," he said.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with a population of some 800,000 and an area of
15,000 square kilometers, had been a Portuguese colony until 1975.
It became an Indonesian province in 1976, but the U.N. never
recognized the move.
</P>
<P>
On January 27, the Indonesian government announced that it is
ready to release East Timor if the alternative to provide wider
autonomy is refused by the people in the region and the
international community.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government has suggested that the U.N.-sponsored
direct balloting to determine if the East Timor wants autonomy or
independence should be held in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
