<HEADLINE> Poor Women Need Help from Society </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 8 (Xinhua) -- More than half of China's 50
million poverty-stricken population are women, and they deserve
more help from all social strata to get out of their plight,
today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quotes Shen Shuji, vice-
chairman of the All-China Women's Federation as saying that more
women are mired in poverty than men, and they find it more
difficult to shake off the shackles of destitution.
</P>
<P>
"In the past decade, anti-poverty campaign initiated by women's
federations nationwide have lifted at least 1.6 million rural
women out of absolute poverty," Shen said at a five-day workshop
on women and poverty which started here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
She said her federation plans to raise another one million poor
women out of poverty by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Between 1990 and 1998, international poverty-eradication aid
projects benefited more than 300,000 rural women in over 20
provinces.
</P>
<P>
While appreciating overseas support, Shen appealed for all
segments of society to launch more development projects to lift
women out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Women rural laborers, numbering 210 million in 1997, account
for 47 percent of China's rural workforce, according to
participants in the workshop.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, about 25 million of the women in rural areas aged
between 15 and 40 are illiterate, preventing them from playing a
bigger role in the country's drive to modernize its agricultural
sector.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, twelve state commissions and ministries
have provided practical skills to 300,000 poor women a year, and
helped three million rural poor women out of poverty, says the
paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
