<HEADLINE> Italy Against Transferring Kosovo Refugees Outside Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Italy said on Wednesday that the
Kosovar refugees should be assisted within the Balkan region,
instead of being transferred to other regions as favored by some
countries like the United States.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema told Sadako Ogata, the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), that the
idea of going to Western countries "is not favored by those
refugees, and would push farther into the future the possibility
for them to return to their homes."
</P>
<P>
The high commissioner, on her way to Albanian capital of Tirana
and Macedonian capital of Skopje, conferred with D'alema on how to
assist Kosovars remaining in the Serbian province of Kosovo and
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
The high commissioner voiced her great appreciation for the
leading role Italy has taken on to coordinate aid in Albania with
its relief operation "Rainbow," in response to the UNHCR appeal.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema informed the high commissioner of relief operation "
Rainbow" which aims at setting up camps along the Albanian border
and the relief items to be stockpiled in these reception centers.
</P>
<P>
After pointing out that the Italian government has never closed
its borders to refugees, D'Alema said Italy is ready and willing
to bring special cases into the country but believes that "all
evacuation measures must be temporary and exceptional and must
come about on a voluntary basis."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Italian Interior Minister Rosa Russo Jervolino,
rejected Washington's plan to ship Kosovo refugees to the U.S.
naval base at Guantanamo, Cuba as one which "would really mean
completing their deportation" and would be "impossible."
</P>
<P>
Jervolino, who met the high commissioner earlier in the day,
argued that these people should not be taken to Cuba but assisted
nearby.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNHCR, about 621,000 refugees have left Kosovo
since the beginning of the crisis in March 1998, with 293,000 of
these displaced in Albania, 136,000 in Macedonia, 60,000 in
Montenegro, 24,300 in Bosnia, 7,000 in Turkey and 100,000 in other
26 countries in Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
