<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' BOP surplus, GIR Level Rise Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' balance of
payments (BOP) had improved further to a surplus of 1.67 billion
U.S. dollars as of March 22, from 1.38 billion U.S. dollars
surplus as of end-February this year, Manila Bulletin reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted officials of the Philippine Central Bank
as saying that the surplus could increase further by end-March to
as high as 1.87 billion U.S. dollars with the expected inflows
from foreign borrowing.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the net international reserves (NIR) as of
March 22 stood at 9.67 billion U.S. dollars, compare to the
end-February figure of 9.39 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Both the NIR and the BOP levels for the period in review
exceed the full-year government's projections with the IMF of 9
billion and 1.6 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The March 22 improvement in the BOP was brought about by the
increased dollar deposits by the national government to the
Philippine Central bank.
</P>
<P>
This was in the form of the proceeds of the government's bond
flotations and some borrowings for the period.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the gross international reserves (GIR) had gone up
to 12.9 billion U.S. dollars as of the end of the last month.
</P>
<P>
A ranking official of the Central Bank had earlier said that
the progress in the trade balance, the volume of dollar inflows,
both portfolio and direct investments, as well as amount of loans
accessed by the government from both the multilateral and
bilateral creditors would spell the difference for the revised BOP
position this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
