<HEADLINE> Queen Elizabeth to Visit Australia Early Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Australia's Head of State Queen
Elizabeth is going to visit Australia early next year at the
invitation of the Australian Prime Minister John Howard, a
spokesperson for the prime minister confirmed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"No date has been set but it is expected it (Queen Elizabeth's
visit to Australia) will be in the first half of next year",
Willie Herron, a spokewoman for the prime minister told Xinhua in
a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
It is probably her last visit as Australia's Head of State as
Australian voters are going to decide in a referendum later this
year whether Australia should become a republic and have their own
president.
</P>
<P>
Buckingham Palace Thursday also confirmed that the Queen would
visit Australia in the first half of 2000 in a visit carefully
timed to avoid controversy as voters decide whether to keep her as
the constitutional monarch, the Australian Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
If Australia votes for a republic, the monarchy would be
replaced by a president on January 2001, the centenary of the
Australian federation.
</P>
<P>
The Queen, who is currently the sovereign of 17 Commonwealth
countries, including Britain's former colony Australia, has always
declined to get involved in the republican debate, insisting that
the question is purely a matter for Australia to decide.
</P>
<P>
Queen Elizabeth last visited Australia in 1992 to help Sydney
celebrate its 150th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Australian Prime Minister Paul Keating then
incensed Australia's monarchists by making what was interpreted as
a pro-republican speech and then placing his arm on the Queen's
back at a reception.
</P>
<P>
His wife Annita Keating breached protocol by not wearing
gloves or a hat to welcome the Queen and failed to curtsey.
</P>
<P>
The incident horrified the British press and caused them to dub
Keating the Lizard of Oz (Australia).
</P>
<P>
Howard, a lifelong monarchist, is unlikely to commit any
similar breach of protocol. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
