<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Ship Monitored by NATO Navy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 7 (Xinhua) - The Russian reconnaissance ship sent
to the Mediterranean was monitored by NATO navy, Russian navy
command said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Liman (Estuary), which left the Ukrainian port of
Sebastopol on Friday, is the first of a seven-vessel flotilla from
the Black Sea Fleet that Russia plans to send toward the Yugoslav
coast.
</P>
<P>
The ship is part of Russia's response to NATO bombing on
Yugoslavia. Its declared task is to "collect information" about
the situation around Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the ship entered the Mediterranean, it was monitored
by navy forces from Greece and Turkey, both NATO member states,
the Russian navy command said. At present, NATO naval vessels
participating in the war against Yugoslavia, and navy forces from
other countries kept watch on it.
</P>
<P>
NATO command was concerned that the Russian ship would sent
intelligence about cruise missiles fired by U.S. and British
vessels and submarines not only to the Black Sea Fleet, but also
to the Yugoslav army.
</P>
<P>
Possibilities of provocations against the ship by NATO
warplanes and submarines could not be ruled out, the Itar-Tass
news agency said, quoting Russian navy experts.
</P>
<P>
They proposed Russia should send additional navy forces to the
waters where the ship was.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that other six vessels of the Black Sea Fleet
had already prepared to sail to the Mediterranean. The Russian
navy command would also study the possibility of dispatching a
flotilla from the North Fleet to the Mediterranean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
