<HEADLINE> Interaction of Intellectuals Boosts Regional Peace: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Frequent interaction between
intellectuals representing Non-Governmental Organizations(NGOs)
can play a significant role in promoting peace and tranquillity in
the region, said Pakistani Speaker of National Assembly Illahi
Bukhsh Soomro Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The speaker expressed this feeling during a meeting here with
President of the Chinese Peoples Institute of Foreign Affairs, Mr.
Mei Zhaorong, who agreed with him.
</P>
<P>
Soomro expressed the hope that Mei's visit would boost
interaction between experienced minds in the two countries in
their efforts to find ways and means for building a better future
for the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Praising the knowledge and experience of the Chinese
leadership, the speaker said that China has made remarkable
multi-dimensional progress during the last two decades and
Pakistan is proud to be one of its closest and most reliable
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
"Pak-China relations are an example of brotherhood, mutual
trust and fraternity in a fast changing world as the two nations
have stood firmly by each other through every test of time," said
Soomro.
</P>
<P>
He added that he is looking forward to the arrival of his
Chinese counterpart Li Peng, which shall be yet another landmark
in Pak-China friendship.
</P>
<P>
Mei, who is leading a four member delegation to Pakistan at the
invitation of Islamabad Council of World Affairs, informed the
speaker that his institute conducts studies on international and
regional issues and interacts with think tanks in other countries
to provide objective analyses and propose remedies to unresolved
conflicts and problems threatening world peace.
</P>
<P>
Thanking the speaker for his hospitality, Mei termed the visit
of Chairman of the National People's Congress Li Peng to Pakistan
as another step forward in the existing fraternal relations
between China and Pakistan. 
</P>
