<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNESCO Against War in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 7 (Xinhua) -- It is not too late to stop the
NATO war against Yugoslavia, said the representative of the
Organization of United Nations for education, science and culture
(UNESCO) in Panama on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a message of the international organization
quoting its director Frederico Mayor Zaragosa, all the parties in
the conflict, including Albanians and Kosovans, should seek a
peaceful solution to resolve the conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Now we have to worry more about the victims of this cruel
conflict, which is ethnically based, where the most vulnerable are
the weakest", he said.
</P>
<P>
In the calls to the international community to close the ranks
in favor of the refugees, UNESCO stressed the nececity to help the
thousands of refugees which are the consequence of the war.
</P>
<P>
Zaragosa said that "today, once again the arms are doing the
talking and thousands of people run the risk of death".
</P>
<P>
UNESCO, reminded that the UN was created at the end of the
second world war to protect future generations from the scourge of
war, and was emphatic in signalling that the mission to establish
in the minds of men was the defence of peace.
</P>
<P>
According to Zaragosa, the grave situation in the Yugoslav war,
has been changed into "a failure for all of us".
</P>
<P>
The international organization gave a call to reason to all the
responsible parts in the conflict, so that the thread of dialogue
could again be begun in the best terms and a peaceful political
solution could be found. "The search for peace in Yugoslavia
should stay as the top priority in Yugoslavia," demanded UNESCO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
