<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Shocks Germany 2-0 at Nigeria '99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian "Flying Eagles" Wednesday
defeated Germany football team by 2-0 at the National Stadium in
Lagos in a tension-soaked match of the on-going 10th World Youth
Championship tagged Nigeria '99.
</P>
<P>
The second-half goals scored by substitute Ganyu Shittu and
Hashimu Garba shot Nigeria to the top of Group A with four points
following the draw match with Costa Rica in the opening game on
April 3.
</P>
<P>
After a barren first half, Shittu, who came in for an injured
Chikelue Iloanusi, made a successful connection of a shot from the
left flank in the 69th minute, leaving German goalkeeper Timo
Heldebrand standing in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
Twelve minutes later, fast attacker Julius Aghahowa broke free
in one of his trademark forays, and his lob into the German 18 was
put past hildebrand by Garba.
</P>
<P>
Though there were still some nine minutes to go, the
celebration had begun. Members of the Nigerian football
supporters club hit their drums with increased intensity and fans
danced away in appreciation.
</P>
<P>
After the match watched by 20,000 spectators, the fans broke
into several groups as they left the National Stadium venue of the
game, singing and dancing as the "Flying Eagles" had won the
competition.
</P>
<P>
Seeking an early goal, the "Flying Eagles" went into full
throttle from the blast of the whistle, piling non-stop pressure
on the Germans and earning at least a half-dozen corner kicks in
the first half alone.
</P>
<P>
The Germans had come into the game cautiously, apparently
hoping for a draw. But they too went for broke after Nigeria's
goals with German striker Patrick Falk running rings round the
Nigerian defence to no avail.
</P>
<P>
The match was not without incident as Nigeria's Iloanusi had to
be taken out of stadium in an ambulance after he was injured in a
clash with a German player. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
