<DOCNO> XIE19990408.0355 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,000-Year Old Cultural Relics Found in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
unearthed a rich vein of cultural relics dating back 1,000 years
in the city of Baoding in north China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
One of the archeologist said these relics were buried under a
three-meter layer of earth at a construction site in the city's
commercial center.
</P>
<P>
The relics include pottery and porcelain articles and building
ruins such as tiles, charcoal, housing foundations, and a
waterspout, he said.
</P>
<P>
This discovery provides a valuable resource for research into
the city's history, architecture, and cultural development during
the Song (960-1279), Jin (1115-1234), Yuan (1271-1368), Ming (1368-
1644), and Qing (1644-1911) dynasties, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ancient city of Baoding was formed during the North Song
Dynasty (960-1127). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
