<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafter Suffers Early Exit at Hong Kong Tennis Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Reigning U.S. Open champion Pat
Rafter of Australia suffered another early exit here Wednesday
when he was ousted by Germany's veteran Bernd Karbacher in full
sets in the first round of the 350,000-U.S.-dollar Hong Kong Open
tennis.
</P>
<P>
Second seed Rafter, ranked fifth in the world, was toppled 7-6
(7-4), 6-7 (1-7), 2-6, and his win-loss record in 1999 is 6-7. He
was off to a slow start similar to last year's performance.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very disappointed because it was a pretty ordinary effort
on my part," said Rafter, who arrived here 24 hours ago from
leading Australia to a 4-1 Davis Cup victory over Zimbabwe in
Harare Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Rafter said: "The conditions here were extremely different to
what I played last week...the court here is faster."
</P>
<P>
After exchanging tie-breaker in the first two sets, 31-year-old
Karbacher played steady game with his powerful returns to Rafter's
backhand, breaking Rafter in the first and eighth games in the
deciding third set to clinch a 6-2 win.
</P>
<P>
Joining the Australian, fourth seed Cedric Pioline of France,
former French Open runner-up, was beaten 6-2, 1-6, 4-6 by Italy's
Laurence Tieleman.
</P>
<P>
World number four Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands
encountered stiff challenge from Takao Suzuki before edging out
the Japanese with an identical score of 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Both players performed serve and volley game but top seed
Krajicek said he could get more confidence and get better as the
competition went on.
</P>
<P>
American third seed Andre Agassi made short work of Italian
Gianluca Pozzi, winning 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Other seeded players Nicolas Kiefer of Germany, Wayne Ferreira
of South Africa and Jonas Bjorkman of Sweden booked their first
round victories Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
