<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fewer Women in Shenzhen Marrying Overseas People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 8 (Xinhua) -- Overseas people seem to be losing
favor with the young women of Shenzhen, the country's first
special economic zone in Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The city had a boom period in overseas liaisons during the late
eighties, but now the city's economic development is offering
young women other opportunities for a better life.
</P>
<P>
The number of women in Shenzhen who married overseas people in
1998 was 651, down from 1,167 in 1988, according to the city's
civil affairs bureau.
</P>
<P>
But what these marriages have lost in numbers, they have
apparently gained in quality as age differences between husbands
and wives are less dramatic than in the past.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 92 percent of the marriages in 1988 were between local
residents and Hong Kong partners, but this figure dropped last
year to only 65 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that fewer locals view marriage as the pathway to a
better life because their current living standards are much higher
than last decade, becoming closer to Hong Kong and some developed
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
