<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Late Equaliser Keeps Man United Alive in Champions League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- A goal in injury time from Ryan
Giggs helped Manchester United with a 1-1 draw against Juventus in
the first leg of the semifinal match of the European Champions
League on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
While in another semifinal match, Bayern Munich also had to be
contend with a draw with Kiev Dynamo on road.
</P>
<P>
But while Bayern's sparked delight for the few travelling
German fans in Kiev, United's brought a wave of relief to Old
Trafford.
</P>
<P>
Bayern had trailed 2-0 and 3-1 but Carsten Jancker's goal to
make it 3-3 put the Germans firmly in the driving seat for the
return leg.
</P>
<P>
Giggs blasted the ball home from close range in injury time to
give United a 1-1 home draw with Juventus who had led through
Antonio Conte's 25th minute shot.
</P>
<P>
Juventus took the initiative from the start at Old Trafford
where United were hoping for a repeat of the 2-0 quarterfinal
defeat of Inter Milan.
</P>
<P>
Unrecognisable from the team which has limped along off the
pace in Serie A, Juve dictated the pace of the game against a
below-par United.
</P>
<P>
The Italians took a deserved lead when Edgar Davids played a
clever through ball for Conte and the Juve skipper shot sweetly
past Peter Schmeichel.
</P>
<P>
Juve continued to dominate, with Davids and fellow midfielder
Zinedine Zidane controlling the midfield and Filippo Inzaghi a
constant threat up front.
</P>
<P>
United, unbeaten in 20 matches in 1999, did not threaten until
the last few minutes when they launched a sustained assault on
Angelo Peruzzi's goal.
</P>
<P>
Substitute Teddy Sheringham deflected a Roy Keane shot into the
net two minutes from time but the goal was ruled out for offside.
</P>
<P>
But, with Juve seemingly set for victory, David Beckham slung a
hopeful cross into the box and after it was half-cleared Giggs
crashed the ball into the roof of the net.
</P>
<P>
Juventus are still favourites to reach the final for the fourth
successive year but Giggs' lifeline left United in with "a great
chance," according to their manager Alex Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
"If we had performed in the first half as we did in the second
we would have been much better off," said Ferguson.
</P>
<P>
"I thought Juventus were outstanding in the first half but we
have to look at our own performance."
</P>
<P>
Dynamo got off to a great start against Bayern when in-form
striker Andriy Shevchenko put them ahead after 15 minutes and then
Kakha Kaladze appeared to touch in a Shevchenko free kick after 43
minutes to make it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
Michael Tarnat pulled one back for Bayern from long range in
first-half injury time but Kiev restored the two-goal cushion with
a stunning Vitaly Kosovsky volley in the 49th minute.
</P>
<P>
Bayern, the runaway leaders of the Bundesliga, continued to go
forward, risking more breakaways by Shevchenko.
</P>
<P>
The adventurous policy paid off when Stefan Effenberg pulled
another back 12 minutes from time and Jancker's third away goal
put them on course for their first European Cup final since 1987.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
