<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ferguson: We've Still Got a Great Chance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Manchester United manager Alex
Ferguson admitted Ryan Giggs had got his side out of jail with his
last-gasp equaliser in the first leg of the European Cup semifinal
against Juventus on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson accepted United had been overshadowed by their Italian
opponents for much of the contest.
</P>
<P>
But he insisted they could still reach the final despite
conceding a goal at home.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Giggs' goal would prove to be a lifesaver, Ferguson
said:"I hope so. I think it does give us a great chance.
</P>
<P>
"But if we'd performed like we did in the second half in the
first it would have been better."
</P>
<P>
Ferguson was full of praise for the visitors: "I thought
Juventus were outstanding in the first half -- all counter-attack.
</P>
<P>
"We have to look at ourselves because every time we made a
mistake they were off in a flash and they gave us a real hard time.
</P>
<P>
"But in the second half our wide players got to grips better in
terms of defending and I think that made a big difference."
</P>
<P>
Ferguson said he had felt fate was against his team, who had a
goal disallowed and had a penalty appeal turned down.
</P>
<P>
"It looked that way for a long time," he shrugged. "On the
offside where the goal was disallowed, the linesman flagged well
after the ball was in the net.
</P>
<P>
"Whether or not it was offside, he was still very, very late
with his flag," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
