<HEADLINE> Internet Use Becoming A daily Essential in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, April 7 (Xinhua) -- Approximately 37 million U.S.
adults use the Internet at home on at least a daily basis,
compared to only 19 million in mid-1997, according to a new study
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The study, based on a nationally representative survey of more
than 1,000 U.S. adults by the end of 1998, also found that the
number of daily U.S. Internet users at work has mushroomed from 19
million to 32 million since mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet has gone from being a curiosity to being a daily
source for e-mail, shopping, research and news," said the study
conductor Strategis Group, an e-data resources and market analysis
company. The group estimates that 84 million Americans or 42
percent of U.S. adults, now use the Internet at home or at work.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, 44 percent of Internet users in the
United States spend less time watching television due to Internet
use. Therefore, there will be a market share war between
television and Internet Web sites for viewship and advertising
money.
</P>
<P>
Adults in 34 million U.S. households now use the Internet a
total of 65 million hours per day, compared to 525 million
television viewing hours for all U.S. adults. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
